# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: electrical-network
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] In electronics, a **two-port network** (a kind of **four-terminal network** or **quadripole**) is an electrical network (i.e. a circuit) or device with two *pairs* of terminals to connect to external circuits.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] Two terminals constitute a port if the currents applied to them satisfy the essential requirement known as the port condition: the current entering one terminal must equal the current emerging from the other terminal on the same port.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The ports constitute interfaces where the network connects to other networks, the points where signals are applied or outputs are taken.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] In a two-port network, often port 1 is considered the input port and port 2 is considered the output port.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] It is commonly used in mathematical circuit analysis.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The two-port network model is used in mathematical circuit analysis techniques to isolate portions of larger circuits.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] A two-port network is regarded as a "black box" with its properties specified by a matrix of numbers.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] This allows the response of the network to signals applied to the ports to be calculated easily, without solving for all the internal voltages and currents in the network.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] It also allows similar circuits or devices to be compared easily.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] For example, transistors are often regarded as two-ports, characterized by their h-parameters (see below) which are listed by the manufacturer.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] Any linear circuit with four terminals can be regarded as a two-port network provided that it does not contain an independent source and satisfies the port conditions.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] Examples of circuits analyzed as two-ports are filters, matching networks, transmission lines, transformers, and small-signal models for transistors (such as the hybrid-pi model).
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The analysis of passive two-port networks is an outgrowth of reciprocity theorems first derived by Lorentz.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] In two-port mathematical models, the network is described by a 2 by 2 square matrix of complex numbers.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The common models that are used are referred to as z-*parameters*, y-*parameters*, h-*parameters*, g-*parameters*, and ABCD-*parameters*, each described individually below.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] These are all limited to linear networks since an underlying assumption of their derivation is that any given circuit condition is a linear superposition of various short-circuit and open circuit conditions.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The difference between the various models lies in which of these variables are regarded as the independent variables.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] These current and voltage variables are most useful at low-to-moderate frequencies.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] At high frequencies (e.g., microwave frequencies), the use of power and energy variables is more appropriate, and the two-port current–voltage approach is replaced by an approach based upon scattering parameters.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] There are certain properties of two-ports that frequently occur in practical networks and can be used to greatly simplify the analysis.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] A network is said to be reciprocal if the voltage appearing at port 2 due to a current applied at port 1 is the same as the voltage appearing at port 1 when the same current is applied to port 2.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] Exchanging voltage and current results in an equivalent definition of reciprocity.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] be reciprocal if it contains active components such as generators or transistors.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] Most often, but not necessarily, symmetrical networks are also physically symmetrical.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] A lossless network is one which contains no resistors or other dissipative elements.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] All the z-parameters have dimensions of ohms.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] For reciprocal lossless networks all the *z*mn are purely imaginary.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] Figure 3 shows a bipolar current mirror with emitter resistors to increase its output resistance.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] Transistor *Q*1 is *diode connected*, which is to say its collector-base voltage is zero.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] Figure 4 shows the small-signal circuit equivalent to Figure 3.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] a simplification made possible because the dependent current source in the hybrid-pi model for *Q*1 draws the same current as a resistor 1 / *g*m connected across *r*π.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The second transistor *Q*2 is represented by its hybrid-pi model.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] Table 1 below shows the z-parameter expressions that make the z-equivalent circuit of Figure 2 electrically equivalent to the small-signal circuit of Figure 4.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The negative feedback introduced by resistors *R*E can be seen in these parameters.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] compared to only *r*O without feedback (that is with *R*E = 0 Ω).
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] only a moderate value, but still larger than *r*E with no feedback.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] In the differential amplifier application, a large output resistance increases the difference-mode gain, a good thing, and a small mirror input resistance is desirable to avoid Miller effect.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] All the *Y*-parameters have dimensions of siemens.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] For reciprocal lossless networks all the *y*mn are purely imaginary.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] This circuit is often selected when a current amplifier is desired at the output.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The resistors shown in the diagram can be general impedances instead.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] Off-diagonal h-parameters are dimensionless, while diagonal members have dimensions the reciprocal of one another.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] For reciprocal lossless networks *h*12 and *h*21 are real, while *h*11 and *h*22 are purely imaginary.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The h-parameters were initially called *series-parallel parameters*.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The term *hybrid* to describe these parameters was coined by D.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] Alsberg in 1953 in "Transistor metrology".
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] In 1954 a joint committee of the IRE and the AIEE adopted the term h-*parameters* and recommended that these become the standard method of testing and characterising transistors because they were "peculiarly adaptable to the physical characteristics of transistors".
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] In 1956, the recommendation became an issued standard; 56 IRE 28.S2.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] Following the merge of these two organisations as the IEEE, the standard became Std 218-1956 and was reaffirmed in 1980, but has now been withdrawn.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] Often this circuit is selected when a voltage amplifier is wanted at the output.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] Off-diagonal g-parameters are dimensionless, while diagonal members have dimensions the reciprocal of one another.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The ABCD-parameters are known variously as chain, cascade, or transmission parameters.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] Note: Some authors chose to reverse the indicated direction of I2 and suppress the negative sign on I2.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] For reciprocal networks *AD* – *BC* = 1.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] For networks which are reciprocal and lossless, A and D are purely real while B and C are purely imaginary.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] This representation is preferred because when the parameters are used to represent a cascade of two-ports, the matrices are written in the same order that a network diagram would be drawn, that is, left to right.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The negative sign of –*I*2 arises to make the output current of one cascaded stage (as it appears in the matrix) equal to the input current of the next.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] Without the minus sign the two currents would have opposite senses because the positive direction of current, by convention, is taken as the current entering the port.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] Consequently, the input voltage/current matrix vector can be directly replaced with the matrix equation of the preceding cascaded stage to form a combined A'B'C'D' matrix.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The terminology of representing the ABCD parameters as a matrix of elements designated *a*11 etc. as adopted by some authors and the inverse A'B'C'D' parameters as a matrix of elements designated *b*11 etc. is used here for both brevity and to avoid confusion with circuit elements.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The table below lists ABCD and inverse ABCD parameters for some simple network elements.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The previous parameters are all defined in terms of voltages and currents at ports.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] S-parameters are different, and are defined in terms of incident and reflected waves at ports.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] S-parameters are used primarily at UHF and microwave frequencies where it becomes difficult to measure voltages and currents directly.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] On the other hand, incident and reflected power are easy to measure using directional couplers.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] where the ak are the incident waves and the bk are the reflected waves at port k.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] It is conventional to define the ak and bk in terms of the square root of power.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] Consequently, there is a relationship with the wave voltages (see main article for details).
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] For antimetrical networks *S*11 = –*S*22.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] Scattering transfer parameters, like scattering parameters, are defined in terms of incident and reflected waves.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The difference is that T-parameters relate the waves at port 1 to the waves at port 2 whereas S-parameters relate the reflected waves to the incident waves.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] In this respect T-parameters fill the same role as ABCD parameters and allow the T-parameters of cascaded networks to be calculated by matrix multiplication of the component networks.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] T-parameters, like ABCD parameters, can also be called transmission parameters.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] T-parameters are not as easy to measure directly as S-parameters.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] However, S-parameters are easily converted to T-parameters, see main article for details.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] When two or more two-port networks are connected, the two-port parameters of the combined network can be found by performing matrix algebra on the matrices of parameters for the component two-ports.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The matrix operation can be made particularly simple with an appropriate choice of two-port parameters to match the form of connection of the two-ports.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] For instance, the z-parameters are best for series connected ports.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The combination rules need to be applied with care.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] Some connections (when dissimilar potentials are joined) result in the port condition being invalidated and the combination rule will no longer apply.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] A Brune test can be used to check the permissibility of the combination.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] This difficulty can be overcome by placing 1:1 ideal transformers on the outputs of the problem two-ports.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] This does not change the parameters of the two-ports, but does ensure that they will continue to meet the port condition when interconnected.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] An example of this problem is shown for series-series connections in figures 11 and 12 below.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] When two-ports are connected in a series-series configuration as shown in figure 10, the best choice of two-port parameter is the z-parameters.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The z-parameters of the combined network are found by matrix addition of the two individual z-parameter matrices.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] As mentioned above, there are some networks which will not yield directly to this analysis.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] A simple example is a two-port consisting of a L-network of resistors *R*1 and *R*2.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] Figure 11 shows two identical such networks connected in series-series.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The discrepancy is explained by observing that *R*1 of the lower two-port has been by-passed by the short-circuit between two terminals of the output ports.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] This results in no current flowing through one terminal in each of the input ports of the two individual networks.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] Consequently, the port condition is broken for both the input ports of the original networks since current is still able to flow into the other terminal.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] This problem can be resolved by inserting an ideal transformer in the output port of at least one of the two-port networks.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] While this is a common text-book approach to presenting the theory of two-ports, the practicality of using transformers is a matter to be decided for each individual design.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] When two-ports are connected in a parallel-parallel configuration as shown in figure 13, the best choice of two-port parameter is the y-parameters.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The y-parameters of the combined network are found by matrix addition of the two individual y-parameter matrices.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] When two-ports are connected in a series-parallel configuration as shown in figure 14, the best choice of two-port parameter is the h-parameters.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The h-parameters of the combined network are found by matrix addition of the two individual h-parameter matrices.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] When two-ports are connected in a parallel-series configuration as shown in figure 15, the best choice of two-port parameter is the g-parameters.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The g-parameters of the combined network are found by matrix addition of the two individual g-parameter matrices.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] When two-ports are connected with the output port of the first connected to the input port of the second (a cascade connection) as shown in figure 16, the best choice of two-port parameter is the ABCD-parameters.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The a-parameters of the combined network are found by matrix multiplication of the two individual a-parameter matrices.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] A chain of n two-ports may be combined by matrix multiplication of the n matrices.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] Suppose we have a two-port network consisting of a series resistor R followed by a shunt capacitor C.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] Certain pairs of matrices have a particularly simple relationship.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The admittance parameters are the matrix inverse of the impedance parameters, the inverse hybrid parameters are the matrix inverse of the hybrid parameters, and the [**b**] form of the ABCD-parameters is the matrix inverse of the [**a**] form.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] While two port networks are very common (e.g., amplifiers and filters), other electrical networks such as directional couplers and circulators have more than 2 ports.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] A two-port network has four variables with two of them being independent.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] If one of the ports is terminated by a load with no independent sources, then the load enforces a relationship between the voltage and current of that port.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The circuit now has only one independent parameter.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The two-port becomes a one-port impedance to the remaining independent variable.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] The negative sign is because the positive direction for *I*2 is directed into the two-port instead of into the load.
[src:electrical-network/abcd-parameters] So, in effect, *I*1 sees an input impedance *Z*in and the two-port's effect on the input circuit has been effectively collapsed down to a one-port; i.e., a simple two terminal impedance.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] In the physics of electromagnetism, the **Abraham–Lorentz force** (also known as the **Lorentz–Abraham force**) is the reaction force on an accelerating charged particle caused by the particle emitting electromagnetic radiation by self-interaction.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] It is also called the **radiation reaction force**, the **radiation damping force**, or the **self-force**.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] It is named after the physicists Max Abraham and Hendrik Lorentz.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The formula, although predating the theory of special relativity, was initially calculated for non-relativistic velocity approximations.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] It was extended to arbitrary velocities by Max Abraham and was shown to be physically consistent by George Adolphus Schott.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The non-relativistic form is called **Lorentz self-force** while the relativistic version is called the **Lorentz–Dirac force** or collectively known as **Abraham–Lorentz–Dirac force**.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The equations are in the domain of classical physics, not quantum physics, and therefore may not be valid at distances of roughly the Compton wavelength or below.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] There are, however, two analogs of the formula that are both fully quantum and relativistic: one is called the "Abraham–Lorentz–Dirac–Langevin equation", the other is the self-force on a moving mirror.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The force is proportional to the square of the object's charge, multiplied by the jerk that it is experiencing.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] (Jerk is the rate of change of acceleration.) The force points in the direction of the jerk.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] For example, in a cyclotron, where the jerk points opposite to the velocity, the radiation reaction is directed opposite to the velocity of the particle, providing a braking action.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The Abraham–Lorentz force is the source of the radiation resistance of a radio antenna radiating radio waves.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] There are pathological solutions of the Abraham–Lorentz–Dirac equation in which a particle accelerates *in advance* of the application of a force, so-called *pre-acceleration* solutions.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Since this would represent an effect occurring before its cause (retrocausality), some theories have speculated that the equation allows signals to travel backward in time, thus challenging the physical principle of causality.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] One resolution of this problem was discussed by Arthur D.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Yaghjian and was further discussed by Fritz Rohrlich and Rodrigo Medina.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Furthermore, some authors argue that a radiation reaction force is unnecessary, introducing a corresponding stress-energy tensor that naturally conserves energy and momentum in Minkowski space and other suitable spacetimes.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Physically, an accelerating charge emits radiation (according to the Larmor formula), which carries momentum away from the charge.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Since momentum is conserved, the charge is pushed in the direction opposite the direction of the emitted radiation.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] In fact the formula above for radiation force can be *derived* from the Larmor formula, as shown below.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Where $\gamma$ is the Lorentz factor associated with v , the velocity of particle.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The formula is consistent with special relativity and reduces to Lorentz's self-force expression for low velocity limit.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The first calculation of electromagnetic radiation energy due to current was given by George Francis FitzGerald in 1883, in which radiation resistance appears.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] However, dipole antenna experiments by Heinrich Hertz made a bigger impact and gathered commentary by Poincaré on the *amortissement* or damping of the oscillator due to the emission of radiation.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Qualitative discussions surrounding damping effects of radiation emitted by accelerating charges was sparked by Henri Poincaré in 1891.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] In 1892, Hendrik Lorentz derived the self-interaction force of charges for low velocities but did not relate it to radiation losses.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Suggestion of a relationship between radiation energy loss and self-force was first made by Max Planck.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Planck's concept of the damping force, which did not assume any particular shape for elementary charged particles, was applied by Max Abraham to find the radiation resistance of an antenna in 1898, which remains the most practical application of the phenomenon.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] In the early 1900s, Abraham formulated a generalization of the Lorentz self-force to arbitrary velocities, the physical consistency of which was later shown by George Adolphus Schott.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Schott was able to derive the Abraham equation and attributed "acceleration energy" to be the source of energy of the electromagnetic radiation.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Originally submitted as an essay for the 1908 Adams Prize, he won the competition and had the essay published as a book in 1912.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The relationship between self-force and radiation reaction became well-established at this point.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Wolfgang Pauli first obtained the covariant form of the radiation reaction and in 1938, Paul Dirac found that the equation of motion of charged particles, without assuming the shape of the particle, contained Abraham's formula within reasonable approximations.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The equations derived by Dirac are considered exact within the limits of classical theory.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The reverse situation, problems in which the fields are specified and the motion of particles are calculated.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] In some fields of physics, such as plasma physics and the calculation of transport coefficients (conductivity, diffusivity, *etc.*), the fields generated by the sources and the motion of the sources are solved self-consistently.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] In such cases, however, the motion of a selected source is calculated in response to fields generated by all other sources.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Rarely is the motion of a particle (source) due to the fields generated by that same particle calculated.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Inclusion of self-fields leads to problems in physics such as renormalization, some of which are still unsolved, that relate to the very nature of matter and energy.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The Abraham–Lorentz force is the result of the most fundamental calculation of the effect of self-generated fields.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] It arises from the observation that accelerating charges emit radiation.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The Abraham–Lorentz force is the average force that an accelerating charged particle feels in the recoil from the emission of radiation.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The introduction of quantum effects leads one to quantum electrodynamics.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The self-fields in quantum electrodynamics generate a finite number of infinities in the calculations that can be removed by the process of renormalization.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] This has led to a theory that is able to make the most accurate predictions that humans have made to date.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] (See precision tests of QED.) The renormalization process fails, however, when applied to the gravitational force.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The infinities in that case are infinite in number, which causes the failure of renormalization.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Therefore, general relativity has an unsolved self-field problem.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] String theory and loop quantum gravity are current attempts to resolve this problem, formally called the problem of radiation reaction or the problem of self-force.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The above expression can be integrated by parts.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] A generalized equation for arbitrary velocities was formulated by Max Abraham, which is found to be consistent with special relativity.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] An alternative derivation, making use of theory of relativity which was well established at that time, was found by Dirac without any assumption of the shape of the charged particle.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Below is an illustration of how a classical analysis can lead to surprising results.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The classical theory can be seen to challenge standard pictures of causality, thus signaling either a breakdown or a need for extension of the theory.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] In this case the extension is to quantum mechanics and its relativistic counterpart quantum field theory.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] See the quote from Rohrlich in the introduction concerning "the importance of obeying the validity limits of a physical theory".
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The integral extends from the present to infinitely far in the future.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Thus future values of the force affect the acceleration of the particle in the present.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The future values are weighted by the factor $\exp \left(-{t'-t \over t_{0}}\right)$ which falls off rapidly for times greater than $t_{0}$ in the future.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Therefore, signals from an interval approximately $t_{0}$ into the future affect the acceleration in the present.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] For an electron, this time is approximately $10^{-24}$ sec, which is the time it takes for a light wave to travel across the "size" of an electron, the classical electron radius.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] One way to define this "size" is as follows: it is (up to some constant factor) the distance r such that two electrons placed at rest at a distance r apart and allowed to fly apart, would have sufficient energy to reach half the speed of light.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] In other words, it forms the length (or time, or energy) scale where something as light as an electron would be fully relativistic.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] It is worth noting that this expression does not involve the Planck constant at all, so although it indicates something is wrong at this length scale, it does not directly relate to quantum uncertainty, or to the frequency–energy relation of a photon.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Although it is common in quantum mechanics to treat $\hbar \to 0$ as a "classical limit", some speculate that even the classical theory needs renormalization, no matter how the Planck constant would be fixed.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] To find the relativistic generalization, Dirac renormalized the mass in the equation of motion with the Abraham–Lorentz force in 1938.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] This renormalized equation of motion is called the Abraham–Lorentz–Dirac equation of motion.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Similar to the non-relativistic case, there are pathological solutions using the Abraham–Lorentz–Dirac equation that anticipate a change in the external force and according to which the particle accelerates *in advance* of the application of a force, so-called *preacceleration* solutions.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] One resolution of this problem was discussed by Yaghjian, and is further discussed by Rohrlich and Medina.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Runaway solutions are solutions to ALD equations that suggest the force on objects will increase exponentially over time.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The ALD equations are known to be zero for constant acceleration or hyperbolic motion in Minkowski spacetime diagram.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The subject of whether in such condition electromagnetic radiation exists was matter of debate until Fritz Rohrlich resolved the problem by showing that hyperbolically moving charges do emit radiation.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Subsequently, the issue is discussed in context of energy conservation and equivalence principle which is classically resolved by considering "acceleration energy" or Schott energy.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] However the antidamping mechanism resulting from the Abraham–Lorentz force can be compensated by other nonlinear terms, which are frequently disregarded in the expansions of the retarded Liénard–Wiechert potential.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The Abraham–Lorentz–Dirac force leads to some pathological solutions.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Here $u^{i}=(\gamma ,\gamma \mathbf {v} /c)$ is the four-velocity of the particle, $\gamma =1/{\sqrt {1-v^{2}/c^{2}}}$ is the Lorentz factor and $\mathbf {v}$ is the three-dimensional velocity vector.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] where $D/Dt=\partial /\partial t+\mathbf {v} \cdot \nabla$ is the total derivative.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] While the Abraham–Lorentz force is largely neglected for many experimental considerations, it gains importance for plasmonic excitations in larger nanoparticles due to large local field enhancements.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Radiation damping acts as a limiting factor for the plasmonic excitations in surface-enhanced Raman scattering.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The damping force was shown to broaden surface plasmon resonances in gold nanoparticles, nanorods and clusters.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The effects of radiation damping on nuclear magnetic resonance were also observed by Nicolaas Bloembergen and Robert Pound, who reported its dominance over spin–spin and spin–lattice relaxation mechanisms for certain cases.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The Abraham–Lorentz force has been observed in the semiclassical regime in experiments which involve the scattering of a relativistic beam of electrons with a high intensity laser.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] In the experiments, a supersonic jet of helium gas is intercepted by a high-intensity (1018–1020 W/cm2) laser.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The laser ionizes the helium gas and accelerates the electrons via what is known as the "laser-wakefield" effect.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] A second high-intensity laser beam is then propagated counter to this accelerated electron beam.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] In a small number of cases, inverse-Compton scattering occurs between the photons and the electron beam, and the spectra of the scattered electrons and photons are measured.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The photon spectra are then compared with spectra calculated from Monte Carlo simulations that use either the QED or classical LL equations of motion.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] The effects of radiation reaction are often considered within the framework of single-particle dynamics.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] However, interesting phenomena arise when a collection of charged particles is subjected to strong electromagnetic fields, such as in a plasma.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] In such scenarios, the collective behavior of the plasma can significantly modify its properties due to radiation reaction effects.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Theoretical studies have shown that in environments with strong magnetic fields, like those found around pulsars and magnetars, radiation reaction cooling can alter the collective dynamics of the plasma.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] This modification can lead to instabilities within the plasma.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Specifically, in the high magnetic fields typical of these astrophysical objects, the momentum distribution of particles is bunched and becomes anisotropic due to radiation reaction forces, potentially driving plasma instabilities and affecting overall plasma behavior.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] Among these instabilities, the firehose instability can arise due to the anisotropic pressure, and electron cyclotron maser due to population inversion in the rings.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] An alternate mechanism for radiation reaction on a point charge accelerated by an external force, is that the charge's increase in energy is diminished by the energy carried away by electromagnetic radiation.
[src:electrical-network/abraham-lorentz-force] This reduces the particle's acceleration without an additional force, and the paradoxes it causes are not there.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] An **AC motor** is an electric motor driven by an alternating current (AC).
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The AC motor commonly consists of two basic parts, an outside stator having coils supplied with alternating current to produce a rotating magnetic field, and an inside rotor attached to the output shaft producing a second rotating magnetic field.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The rotor magnetic field may be produced by permanent magnets, reluctance saliency, or DC or AC electrical windings.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Less common, AC linear motors operate on similar principles as rotating motors but have their stationary and moving parts arranged in a straight line configuration, producing linear motion instead of rotation.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The two main types of AC motors are induction motors and synchronous motors.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The induction motor (or asynchronous motor) always relies on a small difference in speed between the stator rotating magnetic field and the rotor shaft speed called slip to induce rotor current in the rotor AC winding.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] As a result, the induction motor cannot produce torque near synchronous speed where induction (or slip) is irrelevant or ceases to exist.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] In contrast, the synchronous motor does not rely on slip-induction for operation and uses either permanent magnets, salient poles (having projecting magnetic poles), or an independently excited rotor winding.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The synchronous motor produces its rated torque at exactly synchronous speed.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The brushless wound-rotor doubly fed synchronous motor system has an independently excited rotor winding that does not rely on the principles of slip-induction of current.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The brushless wound-rotor doubly fed motor is a synchronous motor that can function exactly at the supply frequency or sub to super multiple of the supply frequency.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Other types of motors include eddy current motors, and AC and DC mechanically commutated machines in which speed is dependent on voltage and winding connection.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Alternating current technology was rooted in Michael Faraday's and Joseph Henry's 1830–31 discovery that a changing magnetic field can induce an electric current in a circuit.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Faraday is usually given credit for this discovery since he published his findings first.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] In 1832, French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii generated a crude form of alternating current when he designed and built the first alternator.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] It consisted of a revolving horseshoe magnet passing over two wound-wire coils.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Because of AC's advantages in long-distance high voltage transmission, there were many inventors in the United States and Europe during the late 19th century trying to develop workable AC motors.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The first person to conceive of a rotating magnetic field was Walter Baily, who gave a workable demonstration of his battery-operated polyphase motor aided by a commutator on 28 June 1879, to the Physical Society of London.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Describing an apparatus nearly identical to Baily's, French electrical engineer Marcel Deprez published a paper in 1880 that identified the rotating magnetic field principle and that of a two-phase AC system of currents to produce it.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Never practically demonstrated, the design was flawed, as one of the two currents was “furnished by the machine itself.” In 1886, English-born American engineer Elihu Thomson built an AC motor by expanding upon the induction-repulsion principle and his wattmeter.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] In 1887, American inventor Charles Schenk Bradley was the first to patent a two-phase AC power transmission with four wires.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] "Commutatorless" alternating current induction motors seem to have been independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] In 1888, Ferraris published his research to the Royal Academy of Sciences in Turin, where he detailed the foundations of motor operation; Tesla, in the same year, was granted a United States patent for his own motor.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Working from Ferraris's experiments, Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky introduced the first three-phase induction motor in 1890, a much more capable design that became the prototype used in Europe and the U.S.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] He also invented the first three-phase generator and transformer and combined them into the first complete AC three-phase system in 1891.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The three-phase motor design was also worked on by the Swiss engineer Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown, and other three-phase AC systems were developed by German technician Friedrich August Haselwander and Swedish engineer Jonas Wenström.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] If the rotor of a squirrel cage motor were to run at the true synchronous speed, the flux in the rotor at any given place on the rotor would not change, and no current would be created in the squirrel cage.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] For this reason, ordinary squirrel-cage motors run at some tens of revolutions per minute (RPM) slower than synchronous speed.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Because the rotating field (or equivalent pulsating field) effectively rotates faster than the rotor, it could be said to *slip* past the surface of the rotor.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The difference between synchronous speed and actual speed is called **slip**, and loading the motor increases the amount of slip as the motor slows down slightly.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Even with no load, internal mechanical losses prevent the slip from being zero.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The constant 120 results from combining the conversions of 60 seconds per minute and that each phase requires 2 poles.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Actual RPM for an induction motor will be less than this calculated synchronous speed by an amount known as *slip*, that increases with the torque produced.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] With no load, the speed will be very close to synchronous.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] When loaded, standard motors have between 2–3% slip, special motors may have up to 7% slip, and a class of motors known as *torque motors* are rated to operate at 100% slip (i.e., 0 rpm, full stall).
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] As an example, a typical four-pole motor running on 60 Hz might have a nameplate rating of 1725 rpm at full load, while its calculated speed is 1800 rpm.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The speed in this type of motor has traditionally been altered by having additional sets of coils or poles in the motor that can be switched on and off to change the speed of magnetic field rotation.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] However, developments in power electronics mean that the frequency of the power supply can also now be varied to provide a smoother control of the motor speed.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] This kind of rotor is the basic hardware for induction regulators, which is an exception of the use of rotating magnetic field as pure electrical (not electromechanical) application.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Most common AC motors use the squirrel-cage rotor, which will be found in virtually all domestic and light industrial alternating current motors.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The squirrel-cage refers to the rotating exercise cage for pet animals.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The motor takes its name from the shape of its rotor "windings"- a ring at either end of the rotor, with bars connecting the rings running the length of the rotor.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] It is typically cast aluminum or copper poured between the iron laminates of the rotor, and usually only the end rings will be visible.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The vast majority of the rotor currents will flow through the bars rather than the higher-resistance and usually varnished laminates.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Very low voltages at very high currents are typical in the bars and end rings; high efficiency motors will often use cast copper to reduce the resistance in the rotor.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] In operation, the squirrel-cage motor may be viewed as a transformer with a rotating secondary.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] When the rotor is not rotating in sync with the magnetic field, large rotor currents are induced; the large rotor currents magnetize the rotor and interact with the stator's magnetic fields to bring the rotor almost into synchronization with the stator's field.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] An unloaded squirrel-cage motor at rated no-load speed will consume electrical power only to maintain rotor speed against friction and resistance losses.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] As the mechanical load increases, so will the electrical load – the electrical load is inherently related to the mechanical load.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] This is similar to a transformer, where the primary's electrical load is related to the secondary's electrical load.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] This is why a squirrel-cage blower motor may cause household lights to dim upon starting, but does not dim the lights on startup when its fan belt (and therefore mechanical load) is removed.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Furthermore, a stalled squirrel-cage motor (overloaded or with a jammed shaft) will consume current limited only by circuit resistance as it attempts to start.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Unless something else limits the current (or cuts it off completely) overheating and destruction of the winding insulation is the likely outcome.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Many washing machines, dishwashers, larger standalone fans, compressors, etc. use some variant of a squirrel-cage motor.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] An alternate design, called the wound rotor motor, is used when variable speed is required.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] In this case, the rotor has the same number of poles as the stator and the windings are made of wire, connected to slip rings on the shaft.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Carbon brushes connect the slip rings to a controller such as a variable resistor that allows changing the motor's slip rate.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] In certain high-power variable-speed wound rotor drives, the slip-frequency energy is captured, rectified, and returned to the power supply through an inverter.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] With bidirectionally controlled power, the wound rotor becomes an active participant in the energy conversion process, with the wound rotor doubly fed configuration showing twice the power density.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Compared to squirrel cage rotors, wound rotor motors are expensive and require maintenance of the slip rings and brushes, but they were the standard form for variable speed control before the advent of compact power electronic devices.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Transistorized inverters with variable-frequency drive can now be used for speed control, and wound rotor motors are becoming less common.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Several methods of starting a polyphase motor are used.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Where a large inrush current and high starting torque can be permitted, the motor can be started across the line, by applying full line voltage to the terminals (direct-on-line, DOL).
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Where it is necessary to limit the starting inrush current (where the motor is large compared with the short-circuit capacity of the supply), the motor is started at reduced voltage using either series inductors, an autotransformer, thyristors, or other devices.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] A technique sometimes used is star-delta (YΔ) starting, where the motor coils are initially connected in star configuration for acceleration of the load, then switched to delta configuration when the load is up to speed.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] This technique is more common in Europe than in North America.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Transistorized drives can directly vary the applied voltage as required by the starting characteristics of the motor and load.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] This type of motor is becoming more common in traction applications such as locomotives, where it is known as the asynchronous traction motor.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] 2. a control-voltage (AC) winding in quadrature (i.e., 90 degrees phase shifted) with the main winding so as to produce a rotating magnetic field.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Reversing phase makes the motor reverse.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] An AC servo amplifier, a linear power amplifier, feeds the control winding.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The electrical resistance of the rotor is made high intentionally so that the speed–torque curve is fairly linear.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Two-phase servo motors are inherently high-speed, low-torque devices, heavily geared down to drive the load.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Single-phase motors do not have a unique rotating magnetic field like multi-phase motors.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The field alternates (reverses polarity) between pole pairs and can be viewed as two fields rotating in opposite directions.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] They require a secondary magnetic field that causes the rotor to move in a specific direction.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] After starting, the alternating stator field is in relative rotation with the rotor.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] A common single-phase motor is the shaded-pole motor and is used in devices requiring low starting torque, such as electric fans, small pumps, or small household appliances.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] In this motor, small single-turn copper "shading coils" create the moving magnetic field.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Part of each pole is encircled by a copper coil or strap; the induced current in the strap opposes the change of flux through the coil.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] This causes a time lag in the flux passing through the shading coil, so that the maximum field intensity moves higher across the pole face on each cycle.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] This produces a low level rotating magnetic field which is large enough to turn both the rotor and its attached load.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] As the rotor picks up speed the torque builds up to its full level as the principal magnetic field is rotating relative to the rotating rotor.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] A **reversible shaded-pole motor** was made by Barber-Colman several decades ago.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] It had a single field coil, and two principal poles, each split halfway to create two pairs of poles.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Each of these four "half-poles" carried a coil, and the coils of diagonally opposite half-poles were connected to a pair of terminals.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] One terminal of each pair was common, so only three terminals were needed in all.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The motor would not start with the terminals open; connecting the common to one made the motor run one way, and connecting the common to the other made it run the other way.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] These motors were used in industrial and scientific devices.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] An unusual, **adjustable-speed**, low-torque shaded-pole motor could be found in traffic-light and advertising-lighting controllers.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The pole faces were parallel and relatively close to each other, with the disc centered between them, something like the disc in a watthour electricity meter.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Each pole face was split, and had a shading coil on one part; the shading coils were on the parts that faced each other.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Applying AC to the coil created a field that progressed in the gap between the poles.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The plane of the stator core was approximately tangential to an imaginary circle on the disc, so the travelling magnetic field dragged the disc and made it rotate.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The stator was mounted on a pivot so it could be positioned for the desired speed and then clamped in position.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Placing the poles nearer to the center of the disc made it run faster, and toward the edge, slower.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Another common single-phase AC motor is the *split-phase induction motor*, commonly used in major appliances such as air conditioners and clothes dryers.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Compared to the shaded pole motor, these motors provide much greater starting torque.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] A split-phase motor has a secondary startup winding that is 90 electrical degrees to the main winding, always centered directly between the poles of the main winding, and connected to the main winding by a set of electrical contacts.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The coils of this winding are wound with fewer turns of smaller wire than the main winding, so it has a lower inductance and higher resistance.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The position of the winding creates a small phase shift between the flux of the main winding and the flux of the starting winding, causing the rotor to rotate.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] When the speed of the motor is sufficient to overcome the inertia of the load, the contacts are opened automatically by a centrifugal switch or electric relay.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The direction of rotation is determined by the connection between the main winding and the start circuit.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] In applications where the motor requires a fixed rotation, one end of the start circuit is permanently connected to the main winding, with the contacts making the connection at the other end.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] A capacitor start motor is a split-phase induction motor with a starting motor capacitor inserted in series with the startup winding, creating an LC circuit which produces a greater phase shift (and so, a much greater starting torque) than both split-phase and shaded pole motors.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] This motor has a centrifugal switch which disconnects the capacitor once the motor has started.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] This motor provides high starting torque.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] This motor provides high starting torque and high efficiency.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] A resistance start motor is a split-phase induction motor with a starter inserted in series with the startup winding, creating reactance.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] This added starter provides assistance in the starting and initial direction of rotation.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The start winding is made mainly of thin wire with fewer turns to make it high resistive and less inductive.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The main winding is made with thicker wire with larger number of turns which makes it less resistive and more inductive.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Another variation is the *permanent-split capacitor (or PSC) motor*.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Also known as a capacitor-run motor, this type of motor uses a non-polarized capacitor with a high voltage rating to generate an electrical phase shift between the run and start windings.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] PSC motors are the dominant type of split-phase motor in Europe and much of the world, but in North America, they are most frequently used in variable torque applications (like blowers, fans, and pumps) and other cases where variable speeds are desired.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] A capacitor with a relatively low capacitance, and relatively high voltage rating, is connected in series with the start winding and remains in the circuit during the entire run cycle.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Like other split-phase motors, the main winding is used with a smaller start winding, and rotation is changed by reversing the connection between the main winding and the start circuit, or by having polarity of main winding switched while start winding is always connected to a capacitor.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] There are significant differences, however; the use of a speed sensitive centrifugal switch requires that other split-phase motors must operate at, or very close to, full speed.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] PSC motors may operate within a wide range of speeds, much lower than the motor's electrical speed.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Also, for applications like automatic door openers that require the motor to reverse rotation often, the use of a mechanism requires that a motor must slow to a near stop before contact with the start winding is re-established.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The 'permanent' connection to the capacitor in a PSC motor means that changing rotation is instantaneous.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Three-phase motors can be converted to PSC motors by making common two windings and connecting the third via a capacitor to act as a start winding.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] However, the power rating needs to be at least 50% larger than for a comparable single-phase motor due to an unused winding.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The synchronous motor can also be used as an alternator.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Contemporary synchronous motors are frequently driven by solid state variable-frequency drives.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] This greatly eases the problem of starting the massive rotor of a large synchronous motor.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Synchronous motors are occasionally used as traction motors; the TGV may be the best-known example of such use.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Huge numbers of three phase synchronous motors are now fitted to electric cars.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] They have a neodymium or other rare-earth permanent magnet.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] One use for this type of motor is its use in a power factor correction scheme.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] They are referred to as synchronous condensers.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] This exploits a feature of the machine where it consumes power at a leading power factor when its rotor is over excited.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] It thus appears to the supply to be a capacitor, and could thus be used to correct the lagging power factor that is usually presented to the electric supply by inductive loads.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The excitation is adjusted until a near unity power factor is obtained (often automatically).
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Machines used for this purpose are easily identified as they have no shaft extensions.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Synchronous motors are valued in any case because their power factor is much better than that of induction motors, making them preferred for very high power applications.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Some of the largest AC motors are pumped-storage hydroelectricity generators that are operated as synchronous motors to pump water to a reservoir at a higher elevation for later use to generate electricity using the same machinery.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Six 500-megawatt generators are installed in the Bath County Pumped Storage Station in Virginia, USA.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] When pumping, each unit can produce 642,800 horsepower (479.3 megawatts).
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Small single-phase AC motors can also be designed with magnetized rotors (or several variations on that idea; see "Hysteresis synchronous motors" below).
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] If a conventional squirrel-cage rotor has flats ground on it to create salient poles and increase reluctance, it will start conventionally, but will run synchronously, although it can provide only a modest torque at synchronous speed.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Because inertia makes it difficult to instantly accelerate the rotor from stopped to synchronous speed, these motors normally require some sort of special feature to get started.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Some include a squirrel-cage structure to bring the rotor close to synchronous speed.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Various other designs use a small induction motor (which may share the same field coils and rotor as the synchronous motor) or a very light rotor with a one-way mechanism (to ensure that the rotor starts in the "forward" direction).
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] In the latter instance, applying AC power creates chaotic (or seemingly chaotic) jumping movement back and forth; such a motor will always start, but lacking the anti-reversal mechanism, the direction it runs is unpredictable.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The Hammond organ tone generator used a non-self-starting synchronous motor (until comparatively recently), and had an auxiliary conventional shaded-pole starting motor.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] A spring-loaded auxiliary manual starting switch connected power to this second motor for a few seconds.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] These motors are relatively costly, and are used where exact speed (assuming an exact-frequency AC source) and rotation with low flutter (high-frequency variation in speed) are essential.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Applications included tape recorder capstan drives (the motor shaft could be the capstan), and, before the advent of crystal control, motion picture cameras and recorders.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Their distinguishing feature is their rotor, which is a smooth cylinder of a magnetic alloy that stays magnetized, but can be demagnetized fairly easily as well as re-magnetized with poles in a new location.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Hysteresis refers to how the magnetic flux in the metal lags behind the external magnetizing force; for instance, to demagnetize such a material, one could apply a magnetizing field of opposite polarity to that which originally magnetized the material.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] These motors have a stator like those of capacitor-run squirrel-cage induction motors.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] On startup, when slip decreases sufficiently, the rotor becomes magnetized by the stator's field, and the poles stay in place.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The motor then runs at synchronous speed as if the rotor were a permanent magnet.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] When stopped and restarted, the poles are likely to form at different locations.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] For a given design, torque at synchronous speed is only relatively modest, and the motor can run at below synchronous speed.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] In simple words, it is lagging magnetic field behind magnetic flux.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] A universal motor is a design that can operate on either AC or DC power.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] In universal motors the stator and rotor of a brushed DC motor are both wound and supplied from an external source, with the torque being a function of the rotor current times the stator current so reversing the current in both rotor and stator does not reverse the rotation.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Universal motors can run on AC as well as DC provided the frequency is not so high that the inductive reactance of the stator winding and eddy current losses become problems.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Nearly all universal motors are series-wound because their stators have relatively few turns, minimizing inductance.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Universal motors are compact, have high starting torque and can be varied in speed over a wide range with relatively simple controls such as rheostats and PWM choppers.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Compared with induction motors, universal motors do have some drawbacks inherent to their brushes and commutators: relatively high levels of electrical and acoustic noise, low reliability and more frequent required maintenance.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Universal motors are widely used in small home appliances and hand power tools.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Until the 1970s they dominated electric traction (electric, including diesel-electric railway and road vehicles); many traction power networks still use special low frequencies such as 16.7 and 25 Hz to overcome the aforementioned problems with losses and reactance.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Still widely used, universal traction motors have been increasingly displaced by polyphase AC induction and permanent magnet motors with variable-frequency drives made possible by modern power semiconductor devices.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Repulsion motors are wound-rotor single-phase AC motors that are a type of induction motor.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] In a repulsion motor, the armature brushes are shorted together rather than connected in series with the field, as is done with universal motors.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] By transformer action, the stator induces currents in the rotor, which create torque by repulsion instead of attraction as in other motors.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Several types of repulsion motors have been manufactured, but the *repulsion-start induction-run* (RS-IR) motor has been used most frequently.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The RS-IR motor has a centrifugal switch that shorts all segments of the commutator so that the motor operates as an induction motor once it is close to full speed.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Some of these motors also lift the brushes out of contact with source voltage regulation.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Repulsion motors were developed before suitable motor starting capacitors were available, and few repulsion motors are sold as of 2005.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Where speed stability is important, some AC motors (such as some Papst motors) have the stator on the inside and the rotor on the outside to optimize inertia and cooling.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Exterior rotors are also common in ceiling fan motors.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] A conical rotor brake motor incorporates the brake as an integral part of the conical sliding rotor.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] When the motor is at rest, a spring acts on the sliding rotor and forces the brake ring against the brake cap in the motor, holding the rotor stationary.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] When the motor is energized, its magnetic field generates both an axial and a radial component.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The axial component overcomes the spring force, releasing the brake; while the radial component causes the rotor to turn.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] There is no additional brake control required.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The high starting torque and low inertia of the conical rotor brake motor has proven to be ideal for the demands of high cycle dynamic drives in applications since the motor was invented, designed and introduced over 50 years ago.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] This type of motor configuration was first introduced in the US in 1963.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Single-speed or two speed motors are designed for coupling to gear motor system gearboxes.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Conical rotor brake motors are also used to power micro speed drives.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Motors of this type can also be found on overhead cranes and hoists.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The micro speed unit combines two motors and an intermediate gear reducer.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] These are used for applications where extreme mechanical positioning accuracy and high cycling capability are needed.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The micro speed unit combines a “main” conical rotor brake motor for rapid speed and a “micro” conical rotor brake motor for slow or positioning speed.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The intermediate gearbox allows a range of ratios, and motors of different speeds can be combined to produce high ratios between high and low speed.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Electronically commutated (EC) motors are electric motors powered by direct-current (DC) electricity and having electronic commutation systems, rather than mechanical commutators and brushes.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The current-to-torque and frequency-to-speed relationships of BLDC motors are linear.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] While the motor coils are powered by DC, power may be rectified from AC within the casing.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] These are two-phase induction motors with permanent magnets to retard the rotor so its speed is accurately proportional to the power passing through the meter.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The rotor is an aluminium-alloy disc, and currents induced into it react with the field from the stator.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] A split-phase watthour electricity meter has a stator with three coils facing the disc.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The magnetic circuit is completed by a C-shaped core of permeable iron.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The "voltage" coil above the disc is in parallel with the supply; its many turns have a high inductance/resistance ratio (Q) so its current and magnetic field are the time integral of the applied voltage, lagging it by 90 degrees.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] This magnetic field passes down perpendicularly through the disc, inducing circular eddy currents in the plane of the disc centered on the field.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] These induced currents are proportional to the time derivative of the magnetic field, leading it by 90 degrees.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] This puts the eddy currents in phase with the voltage applied to the voltage coil, just as the current induced in the secondary of a transformer with a resistive load is in phase with the voltage applied to its primary.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The eddy currents pass directly above the pole pieces of two "current" coils under the disc, each wound with a few turns of heavy-gauge wire whose inductive reactance is small compared to the load impedance.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] These coils connect the supply to the load, producing a magnetic field in phase with the load current.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] This field passes from the pole of one current coil up perpendicularly through the disc and back down through the disc to the pole of the other current coil, with a completed magnetic circuit back to the first current coil.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] As these fields cross the disc, they pass through the eddy currents induced in it by the voltage coil producing a Lorentz force on the disc mutually perpendicular to both.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Assuming power is flowing to the load, the flux from the left current coil crosses the disc upwards where the eddy current flows radially toward the center of the disc producing (by the right-hand rule) a torque driving the front of the disc to the right.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Similarly, the flux crosses down through the disc to the right current coil where the eddy current flows radially away from the disc center, again producing a torque driving the front of the disc to the right.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] When the AC polarity reverses, the eddy currents in the disc and the direction of the magnetic flux from the current coils both change, leaving the direction of the torque unchanged.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The torque is thus proportional to the instantaneous line voltage times the instantaneous load current, automatically correcting for power factor.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The disc is braked by a permanent magnet so that speed is proportional to torque and the disc mechanically integrates real power.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The mechanical dial on the meter reads disc rotations and the total net energy delivered to the load.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] In a split-phase watthour meter the voltage coil is connected between the two "hot" (line) terminals (240 V in North America) and two separate current coils are connected between the corresponding line and load terminals.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] No connection to the system neutral is needed to correctly handle combined line-to-neutral and line-to-line loads.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Line-to-line loads draw the same current through both current coils and spin the meter twice as fast as a line-to-neutral load drawing the same current through only a single current coil, correctly registering the power drawn by the line-to-line load as twice that of the line-to-neutral load.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Other variations of the same design are used for polyphase (e.g., three-phase) power.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Representative are low-torque synchronous motors with a multi-pole hollow cylindrical magnet (internal poles) surrounding the stator structure.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The stator has one coil, coaxial with the shaft.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] At each end of the coil are a pair of circular plates with rectangular teeth on their edges, formed so they are parallel with the shaft.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] One of the pair of discs distributes the coil's flux directly, while the other receives flux that has passed through a common shading coil.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] The poles are rather narrow, and between the poles leading from one end of the coil are an identical set leading from the other end.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] In all, this creates a repeating sequence of four poles, unshaded alternating with shaded, that creates a circumferential traveling field to which the rotor's magnetic poles rapidly synchronize.
[src:electrical-network/ac-motor] Some stepping motors have a similar structure.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] An **electronic component** is any basic discrete electronic device or physical entity part of an electronic system used to affect electrons or their associated fields.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] Electronic components are mostly industrial products, available in a singular form and are not to be confused with electrical elements, which are conceptual abstractions representing idealized electronic components and elements.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] A datasheet for an electronic component is a technical document that provides detailed information about the component's specifications, characteristics, and performance.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] Discrete circuits are made of individual electronic components that only perform one function each as packaged, which are known as discrete components, although strictly the term discrete component refers to such a component with semiconductor material such as individual transistors.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] Electronic components have a number of electrical terminals or leads.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] These leads connect to other electrical components, often over wire, to create an electronic circuit with a particular function (for example an amplifier, radio receiver, or oscillator).
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] Basic electronic components may be packaged discretely, as arrays or networks of like components, or integrated inside of packages such as semiconductor integrated circuits, hybrid integrated circuits, or thick film devices.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] The following list of electronic components focuses on the discrete version of these components, treating such packages as components in their own right.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] Components can be classified as passive, active, or electromechanical.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] The strict physics definition treats passive components as ones that cannot supply energy themselves, whereas a battery would be seen as an active component since it truly acts as a source of energy.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] However, electronic engineers who perform circuit analysis use a more restrictive definition of passivity.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] Then, the analysis only concerns the AC circuit, an abstraction that ignores DC voltages and currents (and the power associated with them) present in the real-life circuit.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] This fiction, for instance, lets us view an oscillator as "producing energy" even though in reality the oscillator consumes even more energy from a DC power supply, which we have chosen to ignore.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] Most passive components with more than two terminals can be described in terms of two-port parameters that satisfy the principle of reciprocity—though there are rare exceptions.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] In contrast, active components (with more than two terminals) generally lack that property.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] Transistors were considered the invention of the twentieth century that changed electronic circuits forever.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] A transistor is a semiconductor device used to amplify and switch electronic signals and electrical power.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] Conduct electricity easily in one direction, among more specific behaviors.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] Integrated Circuits can serve a variety of purposes, including acting as a timer, performing digital to analog conversion, performing amplification, or being used for logical operations.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] A vacuum tube is based on current conduction through a vacuum (see Vacuum tube).
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] Components incapable of controlling current by means of another electrical signal are called *passive* devices.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] Resistors, capacitors, inductors, and transformers are all considered passive devices.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] Pass current in proportion to voltage (Ohm's law) and oppose current.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] Capacitors store and release electrical charge.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] They are used for filtering power supply lines, tuning resonant circuits, and for blocking DC voltages while passing AC signals, among numerous other uses.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] Integrated passive devices are passive devices integrated within one distinct package.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] They take up less space than equivalent combinations of discrete components.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] Electrical components that pass charge in proportion to magnetism or magnetic flux, and have the ability to retain a previous resistive state, hence the name of Memory plus Resistor.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] Sensors (detectors) are transducers that react to environmental conditions by changing their electrical properties or generating an electrical signal.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] The transducers listed here are single electronic components (as opposed to complete assemblies), and are passive (see Semiconductors and Tubes for active ones).
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] Only the most common ones are listed here.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] On a circuit diagram, electronic devices are represented by conventional symbols.
[src:electrical-network/active-electronic-component] Reference designators are applied to the symbols to identify the components.
[src:electrical-network/admittance-parameters] A Y-parameter matrix describes the behaviour of any linear electrical network that can be regarded as a black box with a number of ports.
[src:electrical-network/admittance-parameters] A *port* in this context is a pair of electrical terminals carrying equal and opposite currents into and out of the network, and having a particular voltage between them.
[src:electrical-network/admittance-parameters] The Y-matrix gives no information about the behaviour of the network when the currents at any port are not balanced in this way (should this be possible), nor does it give any information about the voltage between terminals not belonging to the same port.
[src:electrical-network/admittance-parameters] Typically, it is intended that each external connection to the network is between the terminals of just one port, so that these limitations are appropriate.
[src:electrical-network/admittance-parameters] For a generic multi-port network definition, it is assumed that each of the ports is allocated an integer n ranging from 1 to N, where N is the total number of ports.
[src:electrical-network/admittance-parameters] For port n, the associated Y-parameter definition is in terms of the port voltage and port current, Vn and In respectively.
[src:electrical-network/admittance-parameters] where Y is an *N* × *N* matrix the elements of which can be indexed using conventional matrix notation.
[src:electrical-network/admittance-parameters] In general the elements of the Y-parameter matrix are complex numbers and functions of frequency.
[src:electrical-network/admittance-parameters] For a one-port network, the Y-matrix reduces to a single element, being the ordinary admittance measured between the two terminals.
[src:electrical-network/admittance-parameters] The Y-parameter matrix for the two-port network is probably the most common.
[src:electrical-network/admittance-parameters] where YL is the admittance of the load connected to port two.
[src:electrical-network/admittance-parameters] where YS is the admittance of the source connected to port one.
[src:electrical-network/admittance-parameters] and ${\sqrt {z}}=({\sqrt {y}})^{-1}$ is the corresponding diagonal matrix of square roots of characteristic impedances.
[src:electrical-network/admittance-parameters] In these expressions the matrices represented by the bracketed factors commute and so, as shown above, may be written in either order.
[src:electrical-network/admittance-parameters] The above expressions will generally use complex numbers for $S_{ij}$ and $Y_{ij}$ .
[src:electrical-network/admittance-parameters] Note that the value of $\Delta$ can become 0 for specific values of $S_{ij}$ so the division by $\Delta$ in the calculations of $Y_{ij}$ may lead to a division by 0.
[src:electrical-network/admittance-parameters] The two-port S-parameters may also be obtained from the equivalent two-port Y-parameters by means of the following expressions.
[src:electrical-network/admittance-parameters] and $Z_{0}$ is the characteristic impedance at each port (assumed the same for the two ports).
[src:electrical-network/admittance-parameters] Conversion from Z-parameters to Y-parameters is much simpler, as the Y-parameter matrix is just the inverse of the Z-parameter matrix.
[src:electrical-network/admittance-parameters] In this case $|Z|$ is the determinant of the Z-parameter matrix.
[src:electrical-network/admittance] In electrical engineering, **admittance** is a measure of how easily a circuit or device will allow a current to flow.
[src:electrical-network/admittance] It is defined as the reciprocal of impedance, analogous to how conductance and resistance are defined.
[src:electrical-network/admittance] The SI unit of admittance is the siemens (symbol S); the older, synonymous unit is mho, and its symbol is ℧ (an upside-down uppercase omega Ω).
[src:electrical-network/admittance] Oliver Heaviside coined the term *admittance* in December 1887.
[src:electrical-network/admittance] Heaviside used Y to represent the magnitude of admittance, but it quickly became the conventional symbol for admittance itself through the publications of Charles Proteus Steinmetz.
[src:electrical-network/admittance] Heaviside probably chose Y simply because it is next to Z in the alphabet, the conventional symbol for impedance.
[src:electrical-network/admittance] Resistance is a measure of the opposition of a circuit to the flow of a steady current, while impedance takes into account not only the resistance but also dynamic effects (known as reactance).
[src:electrical-network/admittance] The dynamic effects of the material's susceptance relate to the universal dielectric response, the power law scaling of a system's admittance with frequency under alternating current conditions.
[src:electrical-network/admittance] Note that (as shown above) the signs of reactances become reversed in the admittance domain; i.e. capacitive susceptance is positive and inductive susceptance is negative.
[src:electrical-network/admittance] In the context of electrical modeling of transformers and transmission lines, shunt components that provide paths of least resistance in certain models are generally specified in terms of their admittance.
[src:electrical-network/admittance] Each side of most transformer models contains shunt components which model magnetizing current and core losses.
[src:electrical-network/admittance] These shunt components can be referenced to the primary or secondary side.
[src:electrical-network/admittance] For simplified transformer analysis, admittance from shunt elements can be neglected.
[src:electrical-network/admittance] When shunt components have non-negligible effects on system operation, the shunt admittance must be considered.
[src:electrical-network/admittance] In the diagram below, all shunt admittances are referred to the primary side.
[src:electrical-network/admittance] The real and imaginary components of the shunt admittance, conductance and susceptance, are represented by *G*c and B, respectively.
[src:electrical-network/admittance] Transmission lines can span hundreds of kilometers, over which the line's capacitance can affect voltage levels.
[src:electrical-network/admittance] For short length transmission line analysis, which applies to lines shorter than 80 kilometres (50 mi), this capacitance can be ignored and shunt components are not necessary in the model.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p01] Born as a subject to the Kingdom of Württemberg, part of the German Empire, Einstein moved to Switzerland in 1895, forsaking his citizenship the following year.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p01] In 1896, at the age of seventeen, he enrolled in the mathematics and physics teaching diploma program at the Swiss federal polytechnic school in Zurich, graduating in 1900.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p01] He acquired Swiss citizenship a year later, which he kept for the rest of his life, and afterwards secured a permanent position at the Swiss Patent Office in Bern.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p01] In 1905, he submitted a successful PhD dissertation to the University of Zurich.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p01] In 1914, he moved to Berlin to join the Prussian Academy of Sciences and the Humboldt University of Berlin, becoming director of the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute for Physics in 1917; he also became a Prussian and consequently also German citizen again.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p01] In 1933, while Einstein was visiting the United States, Adolf Hitler came to power in Germany.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p01] Horrified by the Nazi persecution of his fellow Jews, he decided to remain in the US, and was granted American citizenship in 1940.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p01] On the eve of World War II, he endorsed a letter to President Franklin D.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p01] Roosevelt alerting him to the potential German nuclear weapons program and recommending that the US begin similar research, later carried out as the Manhattan Project.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p01] In 1905, sometimes described as his *annus mirabilis* (miracle year), he published four groundbreaking papers.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p01] In them, he outlined a theory of the photoelectric effect, explained Brownian motion, introduced his special theory of relativity, and demonstrated that if the special theory is correct, mass and energy are equivalent to each other.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p01] In 1915, he proposed a general theory of relativity that extended his system of mechanics to incorporate gravitation.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p01] A paper that he published the following year laid out the implications of general relativity for the modeling of the structure and evolution of the universe as a whole.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p01] It introduced the cosmological constant and is further regarded as the first step in the field of modern theoretical cosmology.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p01] In the middle part of his career, Einstein made important contributions to statistical mechanics and quantum theory.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p01] Especially notable was his work on the quantum physics of radiation, in which light consists of particles, subsequently called photons.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p01] With physicist Satyendra Nath Bose, he laid the groundwork for Bose–Einstein statistics.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p01] For much of the last phase of his academic life, Einstein worked on two endeavors that ultimately proved unsuccessful.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p01] First, he advocated against quantum theory's introduction of fundamental randomness into science's picture of the world, objecting that "God does not play dice".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p01] Second, he attempted to devise a unified field theory by generalizing his geometric theory of gravitation to include electromagnetism.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p01] As a result, he became increasingly isolated from mainstream modern physics.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p01] Many things are named after him, including the element Einsteinium.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p01] In 1999, he was named *Time*'s Person of the Century.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein was born in Ulm as a subject to the Kingdom of Württemberg in the German Empire on 14 March 1879.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] His parents, secular Ashkenazi Jews, were Hermann Einstein, a salesman and engineer, and Pauline Koch.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] In 1880, the family moved to Munich's borough of Ludwigsvorstadt-Isarvorstadt, where Einstein's father and his uncle Jakob founded Elektrotechnische Fabrik J.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein & Cie, a company that manufactured electrical equipment based on direct current.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] When he was very young, his parents worried that he had a learning disability because he was very slow to learn to talk.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] When he was five and sick in bed, his father brought him a compass.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] This sparked his lifelong fascination with electromagnetism.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Peter's Catholic elementary school in Munich from the age of five.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] When he was eight, he was transferred to the Luitpold Gymnasium, where he received advanced primary and then secondary school education.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] In 1894, Hermann and Jakob's company tendered for a contract to install electric lighting in Munich, but without success—they lacked the capital that would have been required to update their technology from direct current to the more efficient, alternating current alternative.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] The failure of their bid forced them to sell their Munich factory and search for new opportunities elsewhere.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] The Einstein family moved to Italy, first to Milan and a few months later to Pavia, where they settled in Palazzo Cornazzani.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein, then fifteen, stayed behind in Munich in order to finish his schooling.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] His father wanted him to study electrical engineering, but he was a fractious pupil who found the Gymnasium's regimen and teaching methods far from congenial.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] He later wrote that the school's policy of strict rote learning was harmful to creativity.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] At the end of December 1894, a letter from a doctor persuaded the Luitpold's authorities to release him from its care, and he joined his family in Pavia.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] While in Italy as a teenager, he wrote an essay titled "On the Investigation of the State of the Ether in a Magnetic Field".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein excelled at physics and mathematics from an early age, and soon acquired the mathematical expertise normally only found in a child several years his senior.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] He began teaching himself algebra, calculus and Euclidean geometry when he was twelve; he made such rapid progress that he discovered an original proof of the Pythagorean theorem before his thirteenth birthday.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] A family tutor, Max Talmud, said that only a short time after he had given the twelve year old Einstein a geometry textbook, the boy "had worked through the whole book.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] He thereupon devoted himself to higher mathematics ...
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Soon the flight of his mathematical genius was so high I could not follow." Einstein recorded that he had "mastered integral and differential calculus" while still just fourteen.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] His love of algebra and geometry was so great that at twelve, he was already confident that nature could be understood as a "mathematical structure".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] At thirteen, when his range of enthusiasms had broadened to include music and philosophy, Talmud introduced Einstein to Kant's *Critique of Pure Reason*.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] In 1895, at the age of sixteen, Einstein sat the entrance examination for the federal polytechnic school (later the Eidgenössische Technische Hochschule, ETH) in Zurich, Switzerland.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] He failed to reach the required standard in the general part of the test, but performed with distinction in physics and mathematics.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] On the advice of the polytechnic's principal, he completed his secondary education at the Argovian cantonal school (a gymnasium) in Aarau, Switzerland, graduating in 1896.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] While lodging in Aarau with the family of Jost Winteler, he fell in love with Winteler's daughter, Marie.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] In January 1896, with his father's approval, Einstein renounced his citizenship of the German Kingdom of Württemberg in order to avoid conscription into military service.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] The *Matura* (graduation for the successful completion of higher secondary schooling), awarded to him in September 1896, acknowledged him to have performed well across most of the curriculum, allotting him a top grade of 6 for history, physics, algebra, geometry, and descriptive geometry.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] At seventeen, he enrolled in the four-year mathematics and physics teaching diploma program at the federal polytechnic school.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] He befriended fellow student Marcel Grossmann, who would help him there to get by despite his loose study habits, and later to mathematically underpin his revolutionary insights into physics.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Marie Winteler, a year older than him, took up a teaching post in Olsberg, Switzerland.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] The five other polytechnic school freshmen following the same course as Einstein included just one woman, a twenty year old Serbian, Mileva Marić.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Over the next few years, the pair spent many hours discussing their shared interests and learning about topics in physics that the polytechnic school's lectures did not cover.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] In his letters to Marić, Einstein confessed that exploring science with her by his side was much more enjoyable than reading a textbook in solitude.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Eventually the two students became not only friends, but also lovers.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Historians of physics are divided on the question of the extent to which Marić contributed to the insights of Einstein's *annus mirabilis* publications.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] There is at least some evidence that he was influenced by her scientific ideas, but there are scholars who doubt whether her impact on his thought was of any great significance at all.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Correspondence between Einstein and Marić, discovered and published in 1987, revealed that the couple had a daughter named Lieserl.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] She was born in early 1902 while Marić was visiting her parents in Novi Sad.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] When Marić returned to Switzerland the child was no longer with her.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] In a letter written in September 1903, Einstein suggested that the girl was either given up for adoption or died of scarlet fever in infancy.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein and Marić married in January 1903.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] In May 1904, their son Hans Albert was born in Bern, Switzerland.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Their son Eduard was born in Zurich in July 1910.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] In 1912, Einstein entered into a relationship with Elsa Löwenthal, who was both his first cousin on his mother's side and his second cousin on his father's.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] When Marić learned of his infidelity soon after moving to Berlin with him in April 1914, she returned to Zurich, taking Hans Albert and Eduard with her.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein and Marić were granted a divorce on 14 February 1919 on the grounds of having lived apart for five years.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] As part of the divorce settlement, Einstein agreed that if he were to win a Nobel Prize, he would give the money that he received to Marić; he won the prize two years later.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] In 1923, he began a relationship with a secretary named Betty Neumann, the niece of his close friend Hans Mühsam.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Löwenthal nevertheless remained loyal to him, accompanying him when he emigrated to the United States in 1933.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] In 1935, she was diagnosed with heart and kidney problems.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] A volume of Einstein's letters released by the Hebrew University of Jerusalem in 2006 added some other women with whom he was romantically involved.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] They included Margarete Lebach (a married Austrian), Estella Katzenellenbogen (the rich owner of a florist business), Toni Mendel (a wealthy Jewish widow) and Ethel Michanowski (a Berlin socialite), with whom he spent time and from whom he accepted gifts while married to Löwenthal.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] After being widowed, Einstein was briefly in a relationship with Margarita Konenkova, thought by some to be a Russian spy; her husband, the Russian sculptor Sergei Konenkov, created the bronze bust of Einstein at the Institute for Advanced Study at Princeton.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Following an episode of acute mental illness at about the age of twenty, Einstein's son Eduard was diagnosed with schizophrenia.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] He spent the remainder of his life either in the care of his mother or in temporary confinement in an asylum.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] After her death, he was committed permanently to Burghölzli, the Psychiatric University Hospital in Zurich.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein graduated from the federal polytechnic school in 1900, duly certified as competent to teach mathematics and physics.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] His successful acquisition of Swiss citizenship in February 1901 was not followed by the usual sequel of conscription; the Swiss authorities deemed him medically unfit for military service.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] He found that Swiss schools too appeared to have no use for him, failing to offer him a teaching position despite the almost two years that he spent applying for one.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Eventually it was with the help of Marcel Grossmann's father that he secured a post in Bern at the Swiss Patent Office, as an assistant examiner – level III.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Patent applications that landed on Einstein's desk for his evaluation included ideas for a gravel sorter and an electric typewriter.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] His employers were pleased enough with his work to make his position permanent in 1903, although they did not think that he should be promoted until he had "fully mastered machine technology".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] It is conceivable that his labors at the patent office had a bearing on his development of his special theory of relativity.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] He arrived at his revolutionary ideas about space, time and light through thought experiments about the transmission of signals and the synchronization of clocks, matters which also figured in some of the inventions submitted to him for assessment.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] In 1902, Einstein and his friends Conrad Habicht and Maurice Solovine, whom he had met in Bern, formed a group that held regular meetings to discuss science and philosophy.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Their choice of a name for their club, the Olympia Academy, was an ironic comment upon its far from Olympian status.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Sometimes they were joined by Marić, who limited her participation in their proceedings to careful listening.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] The thinkers whose works they reflected upon included Henri Poincaré, Ernst Mach and David Hume, all of whom significantly influenced Einstein's own subsequent ideas and beliefs.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein's first paper, "Folgerungen aus den Capillaritätserscheinungen" ("Conclusions drawn from the phenomena of capillarity"), in which he proposed a model of intermolecular attraction that he afterwards disavowed as worthless, was published in the journal *Annalen der Physik* in 1901.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] His 24-page doctoral dissertation also addressed a topic in molecular physics.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Titled "Eine neue Bestimmung der Moleküldimensionen" ("A New Determination of Molecular Dimensions") and dedicated "Meinem Freunde Herr Dr.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Marcel Grossmann gewidmet" (to his friend Marcel Grossman), it was completed on 30 April 1905 and approved by Professor Alfred Kleiner of the University of Zurich three months later.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] The publications deeply impressed Einstein's contemporaries.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein's sabbatical as a civil servant approached its end in 1908, when he secured a junior teaching position at the University of Bern.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] In 1909, a lecture on relativistic electrodynamics that he gave at the University of Zurich, much admired by Alfred Kleiner, led to Zurich's luring him away from Bern with a newly created associate professorship.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Promotion to a full professorship followed in April 1911, when he took up a chair at the German Charles-Ferdinand University in Prague, a move which required him to become an Austrian citizen of the Austro-Hungarian Empire, which was not completed.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] His time in Prague saw him producing eleven research papers.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] From 30 October to 3 November 1911, Einstein attended the first Solvay Conference on Physics.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] In July 1912, he returned to his *alma mater*, the ETH Zurich, to take up a chair in theoretical physics.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] His teaching activities there centered on thermodynamics and analytical mechanics, and his research interests included the molecular theory of heat, continuum mechanics and the development of a relativistic theory of gravitation.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] In his work on the latter topic, he was assisted by his friend Marcel Grossmann, whose knowledge of the kind of mathematics required was greater than his own.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] In the spring of 1913, two German visitors, Max Planck and Walther Nernst, called upon Einstein in Zurich in the hope of persuading him to relocate to Berlin.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Their invitation was all the more appealing to him because Berlin happened to be the home of his latest girlfriend, Elsa Löwenthal.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] He duly joined the Academy on 24 July 1913, and moved into an apartment in the Berlin district of Dahlem on 1 April 1914.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] He was installed in his Humboldt University position shortly thereafter.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] The outbreak of the First World War in July 1914 marked the beginning of Einstein's gradual estrangement from the nation of his birth.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] However, this expression of his doubts about German policy did not prevent him from being elected to a two-year term as president of the German Physical Society in 1916.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] When the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute for Physics opened its doors the following year—its foundation delayed because of the war—Einstein was appointed its first director, just as Planck and Nernst had promised.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein was elected a Foreign Member of the Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1920, and a Foreign Member of the Royal Society in 1921.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] In 1922, he was awarded the 1921 Nobel Prize in Physics "for his services to Theoretical Physics, and especially for his discovery of the law of the photoelectric effect".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Bose derived the Planck spectrum in 1924.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] That same year, Einstein was elected an International Honorary Member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Britain's closest equivalent of the Nobel award, the Royal Society's Copley Medal, was not hung around Einstein's neck until 1925.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] He was elected an International Member of the American Philosophical Society in 1930.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein resigned from the Prussian Academy in March 1933.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] His accomplishments in Berlin had included the completion of the general theory of relativity, proving the Einstein–de Haas effect, contributing to the quantum theory of radiation, and the development of Bose–Einstein statistics.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] In 1911, he first calculated the gravitational deflection of light passing close to the Sun, a prediction later adjusted upon completion of the general theory of relativity.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] He reworked his calculation in 1913, having now found a way to model gravitation with the Riemann curvature tensor of a non-Euclidean four-dimensional spacetime.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] A total eclipse of the Sun that took place on 29 May 1919 provided an opportunity to put his theory of gravitational lensing to the test, and observations performed by Sir Arthur Eddington yielded results that were consistent with his calculations.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Eddington's work was reported at length in newspapers around the world.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] On 7 November 1919, for example, the leading British newspaper, *The Times*, printed a banner headline that read: "Revolution in Science – New Theory of the Universe – Newtonian Ideas Overthrown".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein began his new life as an intellectual icon in America, where he arrived on 2 April 1921.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] He was welcomed to New York City by Mayor John Francis Hylan, and then spent three weeks giving lectures and attending receptions.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] He spoke several times at Columbia University and Princeton, and in Washington, he visited the White House with representatives of the National Academy of Sciences.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] He returned to Europe via London, where he was the guest of the philosopher and statesman Viscount Haldane.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] He used his time in the British capital to meet several people prominent in British scientific, political or intellectual life, and to deliver a lecture at King's College.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] In July 1921, he published an essay, "My First Impression of the U.S.A.", in which he sought to sketch the American character.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] He wrote of his transatlantic hosts in highly approving terms: "What strikes a visitor is the joyous, positive attitude to life ...
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] In 1922, Einstein's travels were to the old world rather than the new.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] He devoted six months to a tour of Asia that saw him speaking in Japan, Singapore and Sri Lanka (then known as Ceylon).
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] After his first public lecture in Tokyo, he met Emperor Yoshihito and his wife at the Imperial Palace, with thousands of spectators thronging the streets in the hope of catching a glimpse of him.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] (In a letter to his sons, he wrote that Japanese people seemed to him to be generally modest, intelligent and considerate, and to have a true appreciation of art.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] But his picture of them in his diary was less flattering: "[the] intellectual needs of this nation seem to be weaker than their artistic ones – natural disposition?" His journal also contains views of China and India which were uncomplimentary.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Of Chinese people, he wrote that "even the children are spiritless and look obtuse...
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] It would be a pity if these Chinese supplant all other races.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] For the likes of us the mere thought is unspeakably dreary".) He was greeted with even greater enthusiasm on the last leg of his tour, in which he spent twelve days in Mandatory Palestine, newly entrusted to British rule by the League of Nations in the aftermath of the First World War.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Sir Herbert Samuel, the British High Commissioner, welcomed him with a degree of ceremony normally only accorded to a visiting head of state, including a cannon salute.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] One reception held in his honor was stormed by people determined to hear him speak: he told them that he was happy that Jews were beginning to be recognized as a force in the world.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] On April 6, 1922, during a visit to Paris, Einstein engaged in a debate on relativity with the philosopher Henri Bergson.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] This dispute has had widespread ramifications for the humanities and was an academic *cause célèbre* at the time.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein's decision to tour the eastern hemisphere in 1922 meant that he was unable to go to Stockholm in the December of that year to participate in the Nobel prize ceremony.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] His place at the traditional Nobel banquet was taken by a German diplomat, who gave a speech praising him not only as a physicist but also as a campaigner for peace.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] A two-week visit to Spain that he undertook in 1923 saw him collecting another award, a membership of the Spanish Academy of Sciences signified by a diploma handed to him by King Alfonso XIII.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] He was appointed as a German delegate rather than as a representative of Switzerland because of the machinations of two Catholic activists, Oskar Halecki and Giuseppe Motta.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] By persuading Secretary General Eric Drummond to deny Einstein the place on the committee reserved for a Swiss thinker, they created an opening for Gonzague de Reynold, who used his League of Nations position as a platform from which to promote traditional Catholic doctrine.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein's former physics professor Hendrik Lorentz and the Polish chemist Marie Curie were also members of the committee.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] In March and April 1925, Einstein and his wife visited South America, where they spent about a week in Brazil, a week in Uruguay and a month in Argentina.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] In December 1930, Einstein began another significant sojourn in the United States, drawn back to the US by the offer of a two month research fellowship at the California Institute of Technology.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Caltech supported him in his wish that he should not be exposed to quite as much attention from the media as he had experienced when visiting the US in 1921, and he therefore declined all the invitations to receive prizes or make speeches that his admirers poured down upon him.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] But he remained willing to allow his fans at least some of the time with him that they requested.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] After arriving in New York City, Einstein was taken to various places and events, including Chinatown, a lunch with the editors of *The New York Times*, and a performance of *Carmen* at the Metropolitan Opera, where he was cheered by the audience on his arrival.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] During the days following, he was given the keys to the city by Mayor Jimmy Walker and met Nicholas Murray Butler, the president of Columbia University, who described Einstein as "the ruling monarch of the mind".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Harry Emerson Fosdick, pastor at New York's Riverside Church, gave Einstein a tour of the church and showed him a full-size statue that the church made of Einstein, standing at the entrance.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Also during his stay in New York, he joined a crowd of 15,000 people at Madison Square Garden during a Hanukkah celebration.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein next traveled to California, where he met Caltech president and Nobel laureate Robert A.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] His friendship with Millikan was "awkward", as Millikan "had a penchant for patriotic militarism", where Einstein was a pronounced pacifist.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] During an address to Caltech's students, Einstein noted that science was often inclined to do more harm than good.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] This aversion to war also led Einstein to befriend author Upton Sinclair and film star Charlie Chaplin, both noted for their pacifism.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Carl Laemmle, head of Universal Studios, gave Einstein a tour of his studio and introduced him to Chaplin.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] They had an instant rapport, with Chaplin inviting Einstein and his wife, Elsa, to his home for dinner.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p02] Chaplin said Einstein's outward persona, calm and gentle, seemed to conceal a "highly emotional temperament", from which came his "extraordinary intellectual energy".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Chaplin's film *City Lights* was to premiere a few days later in Hollywood, and Chaplin invited Einstein and Elsa to join him as his special guests.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Walter Isaacson, Einstein's biographer, described this as "one of the most memorable scenes in the new era of celebrity".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Chaplin visited Einstein at his home on a later trip to Berlin and recalled his "modest little flat" and the piano at which he had begun writing his theory.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Chaplin speculated that it was "possibly used as kindling wood by the Nazis".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein and Chaplin were cheered at the premiere of the film.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] In February 1933, while on a visit to the United States, Einstein knew he could not return to Germany with the rise to power of the Nazis under Germany's new chancellor, Adolf Hitler.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] While at American universities in early 1933, he undertook his third two-month visiting professorship at the California Institute of Technology in Pasadena.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] In February and March 1933, the Gestapo repeatedly raided his family's apartment in Berlin.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] He and his wife Elsa returned to Europe in March, and during the trip, they learned that the German Reichstag had passed the Enabling Act on 23 March, transforming Hitler's government into a *de facto* legal dictatorship, and that they would not be able to proceed to Berlin.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Later on, they heard that their cottage had been raided by the Nazis and Einstein's personal sailboat confiscated.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Upon landing in Antwerp, Belgium on 28 March, Einstein immediately went to the German consulate and surrendered his passport, formally renouncing his German citizenship.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] The renunciation was at first refused, but the Nazi government finally revoked his citizenship on 24 March 1934.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] The Nazis later sold his boat and converted his cottage into a Hitler Youth camp.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] In April 1933, Einstein discovered that the new German government had passed laws barring Jews from holding any official positions, including teaching at universities.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Historian Gerald Holton describes how, with "virtually no audible protest being raised by their colleagues", thousands of Jewish scientists were suddenly forced to give up their university positions and their names were removed from the rolls of institutions where they were employed.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] In a subsequent letter to physicist and friend Max Born, who had already emigrated from Germany to England, Einstein wrote, "...
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was now without a permanent home, unsure where he would live and work, and equally worried about the fate of countless other scientists still in Germany.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Aided by the Academic Assistance Council, founded in April 1933 by British Liberal politician William Beveridge to help academics escape Nazi persecution, Einstein was able to leave Germany.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] He rented a house in De Haan, Belgium, where he lived for a few months.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] In late July 1933, he visited England for about six weeks at the invitation of the British Member of Parliament Commander Oliver Locker-Lampson, who had become friends with him in the preceding years.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Locker-Lampson invited him to stay near his Cromer home in a secluded wooden cabin on Roughton Heath in the Parish of Roughton, Norfolk.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] To protect Einstein, Locker-Lampson had two bodyguards watch over him; a photo of them carrying shotguns and guarding Einstein was published in the *Daily Herald* on 24 July 1933.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Locker-Lampson took Einstein to meet Winston Churchill at his home, and later, Austen Chamberlain and former Prime Minister Lloyd George.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein asked them to help bring Jewish scientists out of Germany.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] British historian Martin Gilbert notes that Churchill responded immediately, and sent his friend physicist Frederick Lindemann to Germany to seek out Jewish scientists and place them in British universities.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Churchill later observed that as a result of Germany having driven the Jews out, they had lowered their "technical standards" and put the Allies' technology ahead of theirs.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein later contacted leaders of other nations, including Turkey's Prime Minister, İsmet İnönü, to whom he wrote in September 1933, requesting placement of unemployed German-Jewish scientists.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] As a result of Einstein's letter, Jewish invitees to Turkey eventually totaled over "1,000 saved individuals".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Locker-Lampson also submitted a bill to parliament to extend British citizenship to Einstein, during which period Einstein made a number of public appearances describing the crisis brewing in Europe.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] In one of his speeches he denounced Germany's treatment of Jews, while at the same time he introduced a bill promoting Jewish citizenship in Palestine, as they were being denied citizenship elsewhere.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] In his speech he described Einstein as a "citizen of the world" who should be offered a temporary shelter in the UK.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Both bills failed, however, and Einstein then accepted an earlier offer from the Institute for Advanced Study, in Princeton, New Jersey, US, to become a resident scholar.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] On 3 October 1933, Einstein delivered a speech on the importance of academic freedom before a packed audience at the Royal Albert Hall in London, with *The Times* reporting he was wildly cheered throughout.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Four days later he returned to the US and took up a position at the Institute for Advanced Study, noted for having become a refuge for scientists fleeing Nazi Germany.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] At the time, most American universities, including Harvard, Princeton and Yale, had minimal or no Jewish faculty or students, as a result of their Jewish quotas, which lasted until the late 1940s.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was still undecided about his future.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein's affiliation with the Institute for Advanced Study would last until his death in 1955.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] He was one of the four first selected (along with John von Neumann, Kurt Gödel and Hermann Weyl) at the new Institute.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] He soon developed a close friendship with Gödel; the two would take long walks together discussing their work.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Bruria Kaufman, his assistant, later became a physicist.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] During this period, Einstein tried to develop a unified field theory and to refute the accepted interpretation of quantum physics, both unsuccessfully.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] He lived in Princeton at his home from 1935 onwards.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] The Albert Einstein House was made a National Historic Landmark in 1976.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] In 1939, a group of Hungarian scientists that included émigré physicist Leó Szilárd attempted to alert Washington, D.C. to ongoing Nazi atomic bomb research.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] He was asked to lend his support by writing a letter, with Szilárd, to President Franklin D.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Roosevelt, recommending the US pay attention and engage in its own nuclear weapons research.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] The letter is believed to be "arguably the key stimulus for the U.S. adoption of serious investigations into nuclear weapons on the eve of the U.S. entry into World War II".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] In addition to the letter, Einstein used his connections with the Belgian royal family and the Belgian queen mother to get access with a personal envoy to the White House's Oval Office.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Some say that as a result of Einstein's letter and his meetings with Roosevelt, the US entered the "race" to develop the bomb, drawing on its "immense material, financial, and scientific resources" to initiate the Manhattan Project.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] For Einstein, "war was a disease ... [and] he called for resistance to war." By signing the letter to Roosevelt, some argue he went against his pacifist principles.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein became an American citizen in 1940.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Not long after settling into his career at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey, he expressed his appreciation of the meritocracy in American culture compared to Europe.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] He recognized the "right of individuals to say and think what they pleased" without social barriers.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] As a result, individuals were encouraged, he said, to be more creative, a trait he valued from his early education.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein joined the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) in Princeton, where he campaigned for the civil rights of African Americans.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] He considered racism America's "worst disease", seeing it as "handed down from one generation to the next".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] As part of his involvement, he corresponded with civil rights activist W.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Du Bois and was prepared to testify on his behalf during his trial as an alleged foreign agent in 1951.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] When Einstein offered to be a character witness for Du Bois, the judge decided to drop the case.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] In 1946, Einstein visited Lincoln University in Pennsylvania, a historically black college, where he was awarded an honorary degree.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Lincoln was the first university in the United States to grant college degrees to African Americans; alumni include Langston Hughes and Thurgood Marshall.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein gave a speech about racism in America, adding, "I do not intend to be quiet about it." A resident of Princeton recalls that Einstein had once paid the college tuition for a black student.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein has said, "Being a Jew myself, perhaps I can understand and empathize with how black people feel as victims of discrimination".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Isaacson writes that "When Marian Anderson, the black contralto, came to Princeton for a concert in 1937, the Nassau Inn refused her a room.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] So Einstein invited her to stay at his house on Main Street, in what was a deeply personal as well as symbolic gesture ...
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] In 1918, Einstein was one of the signatories of the founding proclamation of the German Democratic Party, a liberal party.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Later in his life, Einstein's political view was in favor of socialism and critical of capitalism, which he detailed in his essays such as "Why Socialism?".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] His opinions on the Bolsheviks also changed with time.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] In 1925, he criticized them for not having a "well-regulated system of government" and called their rule a "regime of terror and a tragedy in human history".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein offered and was called on to give judgments and opinions on matters often unrelated to theoretical physics or mathematics.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] He strongly advocated the idea of a democratic global government that would check the power of nation-states in the framework of a world federation.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] He wrote "I advocate world government because I am convinced that there is no other possible way of eliminating the most terrible danger in which man has ever found himself." The FBI created a secret dossier on Einstein in 1932; by the time of his death, it was 1,427 pages long.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was deeply impressed by Mahatma Gandhi, with whom he corresponded.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] He described Gandhi as "a role model for the generations to come".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] The initial connection was established on 27 September 1931, when Wilfrid Israel took his Indian guest V.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Sundaram to his friend Einstein's summer home in the town of Caputh to meet him.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Sundaram was Gandhi's disciple and special envoy, whom Wilfrid Israel met while visiting India and visiting the Indian leader's home in 1925.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] During the visit, Einstein wrote a short letter to Gandhi that was delivered to him through Sundaram, and Gandhi responded quickly with his own letter.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Although in the end Einstein and Gandhi were unable to meet as they had hoped, the direct connection between them was established through Wilfrid Israel.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein, a Jew, was a figurehead leader in the establishment of the Hebrew University of Jerusalem, which opened in 1925.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Earlier, in 1921, he was asked by the biochemist and president of the World Zionist Organization, Chaim Weizmann, to help raise funds for the planned university.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] He made suggestions for the creation of an Institute of Agriculture, a Chemical Institute and an Institute of Microbiology in order to fight the various ongoing epidemics such as malaria, which he called an "evil" that was undermining a third of the country's development.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] He also promoted the establishment of an Oriental Studies Institute, to include language courses given in both Hebrew and Arabic.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was not a nationalist and opposed the creation of an independent Jewish state.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] He felt that the waves of arriving Jews of the Aliyah could live alongside existing Arabs in Palestine.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] The state of Israel was established without his help in 1948; Einstein was limited to a marginal role in the Zionist movement.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Afterward, Einstein adopted a practical attitude, understanding that "there is no going back", and the new state must be supported.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Upon the death of Israeli president Weizmann in November 1952, Prime Minister David Ben-Gurion offered Einstein the largely ceremonial position of President of Israel at the urging of Ezriel Carlebach.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] The offer was presented by Israel's ambassador in Washington, Abba Eban, who explained that the offer "embodies the deepest respect which the Jewish people can repose in any of its sons".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein wrote that he was "deeply moved", but "at once saddened and ashamed" that he could not accept it.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein did not want the office, and the Israeli government did not want him to accept, but felt obliged to make the offer.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Yitzhak Navon, Ben-Gurion's political secretary, and later president, reports Ben-Gurion as saying "Tell me what to do if he says yes!
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] I've had to offer the post to him because it's impossible not to.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Per Lee Smolin, "I believe what allowed Einstein to achieve so much was primarily a moral quality.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] He simply cared far more than most of his colleagues that the laws of physics have to explain everything in nature coherently and consistently." Einstein expounded his spiritual outlook in a wide array of writings and interviews.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] He said he had sympathy for the impersonal pantheistic God of Baruch Spinoza's philosophy.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] He did not believe in a personal god who concerns himself with fates and actions of human beings, a view which he described as naïve.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] He clarified, however, that "I am not an atheist", preferring to call himself an agnostic, or a "deeply religious nonbeliever".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] He wrote that "A spirit is manifest in the laws of the universe—a spirit vastly superior to that of man, and one in the face of which we with our modest powers must feel humble.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was primarily affiliated with non-religious humanist and Ethical Culture groups in both the UK and US.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] He served on the advisory board of the First Humanist Society of New York, and was an honorary associate of the Rationalist Association, which publishes *New Humanist* in Britain.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] For the 75th anniversary of the New York Society for Ethical Culture, he stated that the idea of Ethical Culture embodied his personal conception of what is most valuable and enduring in religious idealism.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein had been sympathetic toward vegetarianism for a long time.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] He became a vegetarian himself only during the last part of his life.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] In March 1954 he wrote in a letter: "So I am living without fats, without meat, without fish, but am feeling quite well this way.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein developed an appreciation for music at an early age.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] His mother played the piano reasonably well and wanted her son to learn the violin, not only to instill in him a love of music but also to help him assimilate into German culture.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] According to conductor Leon Botstein, Einstein began playing when he was 5.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] However, he did not enjoy it at that age.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] When he turned 13, he discovered Mozart's violin sonatas, whereupon he became enamored of Mozart's compositions and studied music more willingly.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein taught himself to play without "ever practicing systematically".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] He said that "love is a better teacher than a sense of duty".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] At the age of 17, he was heard by a school examiner in Aarau while playing Beethoven's violin sonatas.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] The examiner stated afterward that his playing was "remarkable and revealing of 'great insight'".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] What struck the examiner, writes Botstein, was that Einstein "displayed a deep love of the music, a quality that was and remains in short supply.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Music took on a pivotal and permanent role in Einstein's life from that period on.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Although the idea of becoming a professional musician himself was not on his mind at any time, among those with whom Einstein played chamber music were a few professionals, including Kurt Appelbaum, and he performed for private audiences and friends.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Chamber music had also become a regular part of his social life while living in Bern, Zurich, and Berlin, where he played with Max Planck and his son, among others.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] He is sometimes erroneously credited as the editor of the 1937 edition of the Köchel catalog of Mozart's work; that edition was prepared by Alfred Einstein, who may have been a distant relation.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] In 1931, while engaged in research at the California Institute of Technology, he visited the Zoellner family conservatory in Los Angeles, where he played some of Beethoven and Mozart's works with members of the Zoellner Quartet.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Near the end of his life, when the young Juilliard Quartet visited him in Princeton, he played his violin with them, and the quartet was "impressed by Einstein's level of coordination and intonation".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] On 17 April 1955, Einstein experienced internal bleeding caused by the rupture of an abdominal aortic aneurysm, which had previously been reinforced surgically by Rudolph Nissen in 1948.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] He took the draft of a speech he was preparing for a television appearance commemorating the state of Israel's seventh anniversary with him to the hospital, but he did not live to complete it.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein refused surgery, saying, "I want to go when I want.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] It is tasteless to prolong life artificially.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] I will do it elegantly." He died in the Princeton Hospital early the next morning at the age of 76, having continued to work until near the end.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] During the autopsy, the pathologist Thomas Stoltz Harvey removed Einstein's brain for preservation without the permission of his family, in the hope that the neuroscience of the future would be able to discover what made Einstein so intelligent.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein's remains were cremated in Trenton, New Jersey, and his ashes were scattered at an undisclosed location.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] In a memorial lecture delivered on 13 December 1965 at UNESCO headquarters, nuclear physicist J.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Robert Oppenheimer summarized his impression of Einstein as a person: "He was almost wholly without sophistication and wholly without worldliness ...
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein bequeathed his personal archives, library, and intellectual assets to the Hebrew University of Jerusalem in Israel.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Throughout his life, Einstein published hundreds of books and articles.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] He published more than 300 scientific papers and 150 non-scientific ones.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] On 5 December 2014, universities and archives announced the release of Einstein's papers, comprising more than 30,000 unique documents.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In addition to the work he did by himself, he also collaborated with other scientists on additional projects, including the Bose–Einstein statistics, the Einstein refrigerator and others.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's first paper, submitted in 1900 to *Annalen der Physik*, was on capillary attraction.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] It was published in 1901 with the title "Folgerungen aus den Capillaritätserscheinungen", which translates as "Conclusions from the capillarity phenomena".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Two papers he published in 1902–1903 (thermodynamics) attempted to interpret atomic phenomena from a statistical point of view.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] These papers were the foundation for the 1905 paper on Brownian motion, which showed that Brownian movement can be construed as firm evidence that molecules exist.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] His research in 1903 and 1904 was mainly concerned with the effect of finite atomic size on diffusion phenomena.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein returned to the problem of thermodynamic fluctuations, giving a treatment of the density variations in a fluid at its critical point.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Ordinarily, the density fluctuations are controlled by the second derivative of the free energy with respect to the density.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] At the critical point, this derivative is zero, leading to large fluctuations.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] The effect of density fluctuations is that light of all wavelengths is scattered, making the fluid look milky white.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein relates this to Rayleigh scattering, which is what happens when the fluctuation size is much smaller than the wavelength, and which explains why the sky is blue.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein quantitatively derived critical opalescence from a treatment of density fluctuations, and demonstrated how both the effect and Rayleigh scattering originate from the atomistic constitution of matter.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] The *Annus Mirabilis* papers are four articles pertaining to the photoelectric effect (which gave rise to quantum theory), Brownian motion, the special theory of relativity, and *E* = *mc*2 that Einstein published in the *Annalen der Physik* scientific journal in 1905.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] These four works contributed substantially to the foundation of modern physics and changed views on space, time, and matter.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's "*Zur Elektrodynamik bewegter Körper*" ("On the Electrodynamics of Moving Bodies") was received on 30 June 1905 and published 26 September of that same year.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] It reconciled conflicts between Maxwell's equations (the laws of electricity and magnetism) and the laws of Newtonian mechanics by introducing changes to the laws of mechanics.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Observationally, the effects of these changes are most apparent at high speeds (where objects are moving at speeds close to the speed of light).
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] The theory developed in this paper later became known as Einstein's special theory of relativity.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] This paper predicted that, when measured in the frame of a relatively moving observer, a clock carried by a moving body would appear to slow down, and the body itself would contract in its direction of motion.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] This paper also argued that the idea of a luminiferous aether—one of the leading theoretical entities in physics at the time—was superfluous.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In his paper on mass–energy equivalence, Einstein produced *E* = *mc*2 as a consequence of his special relativity equations.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's 1905 work on relativity remained controversial for many years, but was accepted by leading physicists, starting with Max Planck.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein originally framed special relativity in terms of kinematics (the study of moving bodies).
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In 1908, Hermann Minkowski reinterpreted special relativity in geometric terms as a theory of spacetime.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein adopted Minkowski's formalism in his 1915 general theory of relativity.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] General relativity (GR) is a theory of gravitation that was developed by Einstein between 1907 and 1915.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] According to it, the observed gravitational attraction between masses results from the warping of spacetime by those masses.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] General relativity has developed into an essential tool in modern astrophysics; it provides the foundation for the current understanding of black holes, regions of space where gravitational attraction is so strong that not even light can escape.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] As Einstein later said, the reason for the development of general relativity was that the preference of inertial motions within special relativity was unsatisfactory, while a theory which from the outset prefers no state of motion (even accelerated ones) should appear more satisfactory.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Consequently, in 1907 he published an article on acceleration under special relativity.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In that article titled "On the Relativity Principle and the Conclusions Drawn from It", he argued that free fall is really inertial motion, and that for a free-falling observer the rules of special relativity must apply.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] This argument is called the equivalence principle.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In the same article, Einstein also predicted the phenomena of gravitational time dilation, gravitational redshift and gravitational lensing.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In 1911, Einstein published another article "On the Influence of Gravitation on the Propagation of Light" expanding on the 1907 article, in which he estimated the amount of deflection of light by massive bodies.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Thus, the theoretical prediction of general relativity could for the first time be tested experimentally.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In 1916, Einstein predicted gravitational waves, ripples in the curvature of spacetime which propagate as waves, traveling outward from the source, transporting energy as gravitational radiation.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] The existence of gravitational waves is possible under general relativity due to its Lorentz invariance which brings the concept of a finite speed of propagation of the physical interactions of gravity with it.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] By contrast, gravitational waves cannot exist in the Newtonian theory of gravitation, which postulates that the physical interactions of gravity propagate at infinite speed.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] The first, indirect, detection of gravitational waves came in the 1970s through observation of a pair of closely orbiting neutron stars, PSR B1913+16.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] The explanation for the decay in their orbital period was that they were emitting gravitational waves.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's prediction was confirmed on 11 February 2016, when researchers at LIGO published the first observation of gravitational waves, detected on Earth on 14 September 2015, nearly one hundred years after the prediction.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] While developing general relativity, Einstein became confused about the gauge invariance in the theory.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] He formulated an argument that led him to conclude that a general relativistic field theory is impossible.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] He gave up looking for fully generally covariant tensor equations and searched for equations that would be invariant under general linear transformations only.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In June 1913, the Entwurf ('draft') theory was the result of these investigations.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] As its name suggests, it was a sketch of a theory, less elegant and more difficult than general relativity, with the equations of motion supplemented by additional gauge fixing conditions.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] After more than two years of intensive work, Einstein realized that the hole argument was mistaken and abandoned the theory in November 1915.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In 1917, Einstein applied the general theory of relativity to the structure of the universe as a whole.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] He discovered that the general field equations predicted a universe that was dynamic, either contracting or expanding.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] As observational evidence for a dynamic universe was lacking at the time, Einstein introduced a new term, the cosmological constant, into the field equations, in order to allow the theory to predict a static universe.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] The modified field equations predicted a static universe of closed curvature, in accordance with Einstein's understanding of Mach's principle in these years.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] This model became known as the Einstein World or Einstein's static universe.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] This paper is widely regarded as marking the emergence of modern theoretical cosmology.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Following the discovery of the recession of the galaxies by Edwin Hubble in 1929, Einstein abandoned his static model of the universe, and proposed two dynamic models of the cosmos, the Friedmann–Einstein universe of 1931 and the Einstein–de Sitter universe of 1932.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In each of these models, Einstein discarded the cosmological constant, claiming that it was "in any case theoretically unsatisfactory".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In many Einstein biographies, it is claimed that Einstein referred to the cosmological constant in later years as his "biggest blunder", based on a letter George Gamow claimed to have received from him.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] The astrophysicist Mario Livio has cast doubt on this claim.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In late 2013, a team led by the Irish physicist Cormac O'Raifeartaigh discovered evidence that, shortly after learning of Hubble's observations of the recession of the galaxies, Einstein considered a steady-state model of the universe.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In a hitherto overlooked manuscript, apparently written in early 1931, Einstein explored a model of the expanding universe in which the density of matter remains constant due to a continuous creation of matter, a process that he associated with the cosmological constant.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] It thus appears that Einstein considered a steady-state model of the expanding universe many years before Hoyle, Bondi and Gold.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] However, Einstein's steady-state model contained a fundamental flaw and he quickly abandoned the idea.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] General relativity includes a dynamical spacetime, so it is difficult to see how to identify the conserved energy and momentum.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Noether's theorem allows these quantities to be determined from a Lagrangian with translation invariance, but general covariance makes translation invariance into something of a gauge symmetry.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] The energy and momentum derived within general relativity by Noether's prescriptions do not make a real tensor for this reason.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein argued that this is true for a fundamental reason: the gravitational field could be made to vanish by a choice of coordinates.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] He maintained that the non-covariant energy momentum pseudotensor was, in fact, the best description of the energy momentum distribution in a gravitational field.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] While the use of non-covariant objects like pseudotensors was criticized by Erwin Schrödinger and others, Einstein's approach has been echoed by physicists including Lev Landau and Evgeny Lifshitz.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In 1935, Einstein collaborated with Nathan Rosen to produce a model of a wormhole, often called Einstein–Rosen bridges.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] His motivation was to model elementary particles with charge as a solution of gravitational field equations, in line with the program outlined in the paper "Do Gravitational Fields play an Important Role in the Constitution of the Elementary Particles?".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] These solutions cut and pasted Schwarzschild black holes to make a bridge between two patches.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Because these solutions included spacetime curvature without the presence of a physical body, Einstein and Rosen suggested that they could provide the beginnings of a theory that avoided the notion of point particles.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] However, it was later found that Einstein–Rosen bridges are not stable.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In order to incorporate spinning point particles into general relativity, the affine connection needed to be generalized to include an antisymmetric part, called the torsion.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] This modification was made by Einstein and Cartan in the 1920s.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In general relativity, gravitational force is reimagined as curvature of spacetime.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] A curved path like an orbit is not the result of a force deflecting a body from an ideal straight-line path, but rather the body's attempt to fall freely through a background that is itself curved by the presence of other masses.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] The geodesic equation covers the former aspect, stating that freely falling bodies follow lines that are as straight as possible in a curved spacetime.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein regarded this as an "independent fundamental assumption" that had to be postulated in addition to the field equations in order to complete the theory.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Believing this to be a shortcoming in how general relativity was originally presented, he wished to derive it from the field equations themselves.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Since the equations of general relativity are non-linear, a lump of energy made out of pure gravitational fields, like a black hole, would move on a trajectory which is determined by the Einstein field equations themselves, not by a new law.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Accordingly, Einstein proposed that the field equations would determine the path of a singular solution, like a black hole, to be a geodesic.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Both physicists and philosophers have often repeated the assertion that the geodesic equation can be obtained from applying the field equations to the motion of a gravitational singularity, but this claim remains disputed.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In a 1905 paper, Einstein postulated that light itself consists of localized particles (*quanta*).
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's light quanta were nearly universally rejected by all physicists, including Max Planck and Niels Bohr.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] This idea only became universally accepted in 1919, with Robert Millikan's detailed experiments on the photoelectric effect, and with the measurement of Compton scattering.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein concluded that each wave of frequency *f* is associated with a collection of photons with energy *hf* each, where *h* is the Planck constant.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] He did not say much more, because he was not sure how the particles were related to the wave.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] But he did suggest that this idea would explain certain experimental results, notably the photoelectric effect.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Light quanta were dubbed *photons* by Gilbert N.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In 1907, Einstein proposed a model of matter where each atom in a lattice structure is an independent harmonic oscillator.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In the Einstein model, each atom oscillates independently—a series of equally spaced quantized states for each oscillator.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein was aware that getting the frequency of the actual oscillations would be difficult, but he nevertheless proposed this theory because it was a particularly clear demonstration that quantum mechanics could solve the specific heat problem in classical mechanics.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In 1924, Einstein received a description of a statistical model from Indian physicist Satyendra Nath Bose, based on a counting method that assumed that light could be understood as a gas of indistinguishable particles.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein noted that Bose's statistics applied to some atoms as well as to the proposed light particles, and submitted his translation of Bose's paper to the *Zeitschrift für Physik*.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein also published his own articles describing the model and its implications, among them the Bose–Einstein condensate phenomenon that some particulates should appear at very low temperatures.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] It was not until 1995 that the first such condensate was produced experimentally by Eric Allin Cornell and Carl Wieman using ultra-cooling equipment built at the NIST–JILA laboratory at the University of Colorado at Boulder.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Bose–Einstein statistics are now used to describe the behaviors of any assembly of bosons.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's sketches for this project may be seen in the Einstein Archive in the library of the Leiden University.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Although the patent office promoted Einstein to Technical Examiner Second Class in 1906, he had not given up on academia.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In 1908, he became a *Privatdozent* at the University of Bern.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] This paper introduced the *photon* concept and inspired the notion of wave–particle duality in quantum mechanics.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein saw this wave–particle duality in radiation as concrete evidence for his conviction that physics needed a new, unified foundation.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In a series of works completed from 1911 to 1913, Planck reformulated his 1900 quantum theory and introduced the idea of zero-point energy in his "second quantum theory".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Soon, this idea attracted the attention of Einstein and his assistant Otto Stern.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Assuming the energy of rotating diatomic molecules contains zero-point energy, they then compared the theoretical specific heat of hydrogen gas with the experimental data.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] However, after publishing the findings, they promptly withdrew their support, because they no longer had confidence in the correctness of the idea of zero-point energy.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In 1917, at the height of his work on relativity, Einstein published an article in *Physikalische Zeitschrift* that proposed the possibility of stimulated emission, the physical process that makes possible the maser and the laser.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] This article showed that the statistics of absorption and emission of light would only be consistent with Planck's distribution law if the emission of light into a mode with n photons would be enhanced statistically compared to the emission of light into an empty mode.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] This paper was enormously influential in the later development of quantum mechanics, because it was the first paper to show that the statistics of atomic transitions had simple laws.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein discovered Louis de Broglie's work and supported his ideas, which were received skeptically at first.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In another major paper from this era, Einstein observed that de Broglie waves could explain the quantization rules of Bohr and Sommerfeld.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] This paper would inspire Schrödinger's work of 1926.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein played a major role in developing quantum theory, beginning with his 1905 paper on the photoelectric effect.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] However, he became displeased with modern quantum mechanics as it had evolved after 1925, despite its acceptance by other physicists.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] He was skeptical that the randomness of quantum mechanics was fundamental rather than the result of determinism, stating that God "is not playing at dice".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Until the end of his life, he continued to maintain that quantum mechanics was incomplete.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] The Bohr–Einstein debates were a series of public disputes about quantum mechanics between Einstein and Niels Bohr, who were two of its founders.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Their debates are remembered because of their importance to the philosophy of science.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Their debates would influence later interpretations of quantum mechanics.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein never fully accepted quantum mechanics.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] While he recognized that it made correct predictions, he believed a more fundamental description of nature must be possible.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Over the years he presented multiple arguments to this effect, but the one he preferred most dated to a debate with Bohr in 1930.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein suggested a thought experiment in which two objects are allowed to interact and then moved apart a great distance from each other.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] The quantum-mechanical description of the two objects is a mathematical entity known as a wavefunction.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] If the wavefunction that describes the two objects before their interaction is given, then the Schrödinger equation provides the wavefunction that describes them after their interaction.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] But because of what would later be called quantum entanglement, measuring one object would lead to an instantaneous change of the wavefunction describing the other object, no matter how far away it is.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Moreover, the choice of which measurement to perform upon the first object would affect what wavefunction could result for the second object.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein reasoned that no influence could propagate from the first object to the second instantaneously fast.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Indeed, he argued, physics depends on being able to tell one thing apart from another, and such instantaneous influences would call that into question.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Because the true "physical condition" of the second object could not be immediately altered by an action done to the first, Einstein concluded, the wavefunction could not be that true physical condition, only an incomplete description of it.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] A more famous version of this argument came in 1935, when Einstein published a paper with Boris Podolsky and Nathan Rosen that laid out what would become known as the EPR paradox.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In this thought experiment, two particles interact in such a way that the wavefunction describing them is entangled.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Then, no matter how far the two particles were separated, a precise position measurement on one particle would imply the ability to predict, perfectly, the result of measuring the position of the other particle.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Likewise, a precise momentum measurement of one particle would result in an equally precise prediction for of the momentum of the other particle, without needing to disturb the other particle in any way.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] They argued that no action taken on the first particle could instantaneously affect the other, since this would involve information being transmitted faster than light, which is forbidden by the theory of relativity.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] But quantum mechanics considers these two observables incompatible and thus does not associate simultaneous values for both to any system.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein, Podolsky, and Rosen therefore concluded that quantum theory does not provide a complete description of reality.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In 1964, John Stewart Bell carried the analysis of quantum entanglement much further.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] He deduced that if measurements are performed independently on the two separated particles of an entangled pair, then the assumption that the outcomes depend upon hidden variables within each half implies a mathematical constraint on how the outcomes on the two measurements are correlated.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] This constraint would later be called a Bell inequality.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Bell then showed that quantum physics predicts correlations that violate this inequality.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Consequently, the only way that hidden variables could explain the predictions of quantum physics is if they are "nonlocal", which is to say that somehow the two particles are able to interact instantaneously no matter how widely they ever become separated.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Bell argued that because an explanation of quantum phenomena in terms of hidden variables would require nonlocality, the EPR paradox "is resolved in the way which Einstein would have liked least".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Despite this, and although Einstein personally found the argument in the EPR paper overly complicated, that paper became among the most influential papers published in *Physical Review*.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] It is considered a centerpiece of the development of quantum information theory.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Encouraged by his success with general relativity, Einstein sought an even more ambitious geometrical theory that would treat gravitation and electromagnetism as aspects of a single entity.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In 1950, he described his unified field theory in a *Scientific American* article titled "On the Generalized Theory of Gravitation".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] His attempt to find the most fundamental laws of nature won him praise but not success: a particularly conspicuous blemish of his model was that it did not accommodate the strong and weak nuclear forces, neither of which was well understood until many years after his death.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Although most researchers now believe that Einstein's approach to unifying physics was mistaken, his goal of a theory of everything is one to which his successors still aspire.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein conducted other investigations that were unsuccessful and abandoned.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] These pertain to force, superconductivity, and other research.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In addition to longtime collaborators Leopold Infeld, Nathan Rosen, Peter Bergmann and others, Einstein also had some one-shot collaborations with various scientists.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In 1908, Owen Willans Richardson predicted that a change in the magnetic moment of a free body will cause this body to rotate.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] This effect is a consequence of the conservation of angular momentum and is strong enough to be observable in ferromagnetic materials.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein and Wander Johannes de Haas published two papers in 1915 claiming the first experimental observation of the effect.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Measurements of this kind demonstrate that the phenomenon of magnetization is caused by the alignment (polarization) of the angular momenta of the electrons in the material along the axis of magnetization.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] These measurements also allow the separation of the two contributions to the magnetization: that which is associated with the spin and with the orbital motion of the electrons.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] The Einstein-de Haas experiment is the only experiment conceived, realized and published by Albert Einstein himself.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] A complete original version of the Einstein-de Haas experimental equipment was donated by Geertruida de Haas-Lorentz, wife of de Haas and daughter of Lorentz, to the Ampère Museum in Lyon France in 1961 where it is currently on display.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] It was lost among the museum's holdings and was rediscovered in 2023.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In 1926, Einstein and his former student Leó Szilárd co-invented (and in 1930, patented) the Einstein refrigerator.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] This absorption refrigerator was then revolutionary for having no moving parts and using only heat as an input.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] On 11 November 1930, U.S. patent 1,781,541 was awarded to Einstein and Leó Szilárd for the refrigerator.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Their invention was not immediately put into commercial production, but the most promising of their patents were acquired by the Swedish company Electrolux.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein also invented an electromagnetic pump, sound reproduction device, and several other household devices.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] While traveling, Einstein wrote daily to his wife Elsa and adopted stepdaughters Margot and Ilse.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] The letters were included in the papers bequeathed to the Hebrew University of Jerusalem.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Margot Einstein permitted the personal letters to be made available to the public, but requested that it not be done until twenty years after her death (she died in 1986).
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Barbara Wolff, of the Hebrew University's Albert Einstein Archives, told the BBC that there are about 3,500 pages of private correspondence written between 1912 and 1955.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In his final four years, Einstein was involved with the establishment of the Albert Einstein College of Medicine in New York City.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In 1979, the Albert Einstein Memorial was unveiled outside the National Academy of Sciences building in Washington, D.C. for the Einstein centenary.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein can be seen holding a paper with three of his most important equations: for the photoelectric effect, general relativity and mass-energy equivalence.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's right of publicity was litigated in 2015 in a federal district court in California.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Although the court initially held that the right had expired, that ruling was immediately appealed, and the decision was later vacated in its entirety.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] The underlying claims between the parties in that lawsuit were ultimately settled.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] The right is enforceable, and the Hebrew University of Jerusalem is the exclusive representative of that right.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Corbis, successor to The Roger Richman Agency, licenses the use of his name and associated imagery, as agent for the university.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Mount Einstein in the Chugach Mountains of Alaska was named in 1955.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Mount Einstein in New Zealand's Paparoa Range was named after him in 1970 by the Department of Scientific and Industrial Research.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In 1999, Einstein was named *Time*'s Person of the Century.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In 1999, a survey of the top 100 physicists voted for Einstein as the "greatest physicist ever", while a parallel survey of rank-and-file physicists gave the top spot to Isaac Newton, with Einstein second.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Simmons ranked Einstein second after Newton in *The Scientific 100*, based on a qualitative assessment in which he ordered the scientists according to overall influence, and noted that the work of Einstein "forms the source of twentieth-century physics".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] The International Union of Pure and Applied Physics declared 2005 the "World Year of Physics", also known as "Einstein Year", in recognition of Einstein's "miracle year" in 1905.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] It was also declared the "International Year of Physics" by the United Nations.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein became one of the most famous scientific celebrities after the confirmation of his general theory of relativity in 1919.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Although most of the public had little understanding of his work, he was widely recognized and admired.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] In the period before World War II, *The New Yorker* published a vignette in their "The Talk of the Town" feature saying that Einstein was so well known in America that he would be stopped on the street by people wanting him to explain "that theory".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Eventually he came to cope with unwanted enquirers by pretending to be someone else: "Pardon me, sorry!
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein has been the subject of or inspiration for many novels, films, plays, and works of music.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] He is a favorite model for depictions of absent-minded professors; his expressive face and distinctive hairstyle have been widely copied and exaggerated.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] *Time* magazine's Frederic Golden wrote that Einstein was "a cartoonist's dream come true".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] His intellectual achievements and originality made *Einstein* broadly synonymous with *genius*.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Many popular quotations are often misattributed to him.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein received numerous awards and honors, and in 1922, he was awarded the 1921 Nobel Prize in Physics "for his services to Theoretical Physics, and especially for his discovery of the law of the photoelectric effect".
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] The Nobel committee decided that none of the nominations in 1921 met the criteria set by Alfred Nobel, so the 1921 prize was carried forward and awarded to Einstein in 1922.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] Einsteinium, a synthetic chemical element, was named in his honor in 1955, a few months after his death.
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] (Public Domain) *Einstein, Albert (1926).
[src:electrical-network/albert-einstein-p04] London & New York: The Encyclopædia Britannica Company. pp.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] An **electrical circuit** is a network consisting of a closed loop, giving a return path for the current.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] Thus all circuits are networks, but not all networks are circuits (although networks without a closed loop are often referred to as **open circuits**).
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] A *resistive network* is a network containing only resistors and ideal current and voltage sources.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] Analysis of resistive networks is less complicated than analysis of networks containing capacitors and inductors.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] If the sources are constant (DC) sources, the result is a DC network.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] The effective resistance and current distribution properties of arbitrary resistor networks can be modeled in terms of their graph measures and geometrical properties.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] A network that contains active electronic components is known as an *electronic circuit*.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] Such networks are generally nonlinear and require more complex design and analysis tools.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] An active network contains at least one voltage source or current source that can supply energy to the network indefinitely.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] A passive network does not contain an active source.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] An active network contains one or more sources of electromotive force.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] Practical examples of such sources include a battery or a generator.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] Active elements can inject power to the circuit, provide power gain, and control the current flow within the circuit.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] Passive networks do not contain any sources of electromotive force.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] They consist of passive elements like resistors and capacitors.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] Linear electrical networks, a special type consisting only of sources (voltage or current), linear lumped elements (resistors, capacitors, inductors), and linear distributed elements (transmission lines), have the property that signals are linearly superimposable.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] They are thus more easily analyzed, using powerful frequency domain methods such as Laplace transforms, to determine DC response, AC response, and transient response.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] Passive networks are generally taken to be linear, but there are exceptions.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] For instance, an inductor with an iron core can be driven into saturation if driven with a large enough current.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] In this region, the behaviour of the inductor is very non-linear.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] Discrete passive components (resistors, capacitors and inductors) are called *lumped elements* because all of their, respectively, resistance, capacitance and inductance is assumed to be located ("lumped") at one place.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] This design philosophy is called the lumped-element model and networks so designed are called *lumped-element circuits*.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] This is the conventional approach to circuit design.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] At high enough frequencies, or for long enough circuits (such as power transmission lines), the lumped assumption no longer holds because there is a significant fraction of a wavelength across the component dimensions.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] A new design model, called the distributed-element model, is needed for such cases.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] Networks designed to this model are called *distributed-element circuits*.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] A distributed-element circuit that includes some lumped components is called a *semi-lumped* design.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] An example of a semi-lumped circuit is the combline filter.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] Sources can be classified as independent sources and dependent sources.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] An ideal independent source maintains the same voltage or current regardless of the other elements present in the circuit.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] Its value is either constant (DC) or sinusoidal (AC).
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] The strength of voltage or current is not changed by any variation in the connected network.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] Dependent sources depend upon a particular element of the circuit for delivering the power or voltage or current, depending upon the type of source it is.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] A number of electrical laws apply to all linear resistive networks.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] Applying these laws results in a set of simultaneous equations that can be solved either algebraically or numerically.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] The laws can generally be extended to networks containing reactances.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] They cannot be used in networks that contain nonlinear or time-varying components.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] To design any electrical circuit, either analog or digital, electrical engineers need to be able to predict the voltages and currents at all places within the circuit.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] Simple linear circuits can be analyzed by hand using complex number theory.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] In more complex cases, the circuit may be analyzed with specialized computer programs or estimation techniques such as the piecewise-linear model.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] Circuit simulation software, such as HSPICE (an analog circuit simulator), and languages such as VHDL-AMS and verilog-AMS allow engineers to design circuits without the time, cost and risk of error involved in building circuit prototypes.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] More complex circuits can be analyzed numerically with software such as SPICE or GNUCAP, or symbolically using software such as SapWin.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] When faced with a new circuit, the software first tries to find a steady state solution, that is, one where all nodes conform to Kirchhoff's current law *and* the voltages across and through each element of the circuit conform to the voltage/current equations governing that element.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] Once the steady state solution is found, the *operating points* of each element in the circuit are known.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] For a small signal analysis, every non-linear element can be linearized around its operation point to obtain the small-signal estimate of the voltages and currents.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] The resulting linear circuit matrix can be solved with Gaussian elimination.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] Software such as the PLECS interface to Simulink uses piecewise-linear approximation of the equations governing the elements of a circuit.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] The circuit is treated as a completely linear network of ideal diodes.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] Every time a diode switches from on to off or vice versa, the configuration of the linear network changes.
[src:electrical-network/electrical-network] Adding more detail to the approximation of equations increases the accuracy of the simulation, but also increases its running time.
